<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR Confirms Possible Clash Between Rival Serb Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 18 (Xinhua)--NATO-led Stabilization
Force(SFOR) confirmed on Monday that its troops had been
developed around the Banja Luka police station to prevent a
potential clash between rival Serb police.
</P>
<P>
Major John Blakeley, a spokesman for SFOR, said that after 50
Serb special policemen loyal to Republika Srpska President
Biljana Plavsic took over the Banja Luka public security center
in a predawn raid on Sunday, Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb member
of the Bosnia presidency asked SFOR for permission to use other
special police units for "operational reason".
</P>
<P>
SFOR denied the request and deployed two platoons of military
police equipped with eight armored vehicles around the police
station to prevent a "potentially explosive situation from
developing", Blakeley said.
</P>
<P>
The special police, who claimed to have found evidence in the
station of espionage on Plavsic by her opponents, were later
escorted back to their barracks by SFOR troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Rallies Arab Backing in Fighting Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat today called for Arab action in face of
Israeli sanctions against the Palestinians in a message he sent to
the 22-member Arab League (AL).
</P>
<P>
"The message examined the latest negative developments in the
Palestinian territories due to the Israeli anti-peace coercive
measures and its imposing of a starvation policy and embargo
against the Palestinians," the Egyptian MENA news agency quoted
PNA permanent representative to the Arab League Mohammad Subeih as
saying.
</P>
<P>
It comes in the light of perpetual attempts by Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's government to intimidate the PNA and
spark off a civil war among the Palestinians, said Subeih after
handing over the message to AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul
Meguid.
</P>
<P>
Meguid briefed the Palestinian representative on his recent
intensive contacts with Arab foreign ministers and permanent UN
Security Council member states in order to support the PNA and
foil Netanyahu's schemes, according to MENA.
</P>
<P>
Arafat accused Israel of waging "state terrorism" against his
people as punishment for July 30 double suicide bombing in Jewish
west Jerusalem and urged last week an emergency Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein and United Arab Emirates
President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan al Nahyan were involved in
efforts to convene the summit to discuss the Israeli-Palestinian
peace-making crisis.
</P>
<P>
The bombing attack took place just as the Israelis and the
Palestinians decided to resume the peace talks, which had been
stopped by the construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the bombing attack, Israel sealed off
Palestinian areas, froze millions of dollars of financial
transfers it owes the PNA and suspended the resumption of talks
with the PNA on so-called confidence building measures such as
opening air and sea ports in self-ruled Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has threatened to match the sanctions with a partial
boycott of Israeli goods and go on with "national unity" talks
with various Palestinian groups on Wednesday despite Israeli
accusation that the talks amount to "appeasement of terrorism."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
