<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Appeals for Ending of Fighting in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- France today again called for an
immediate ending of fighting in northwest of Cambodia between the
forces loyal to former First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh
allied with the Khmer Rouge and those of Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
"We remain particularly vigilant in respect of the situation
of human rights and appeal from our hearts the rapid and concrete
improvement in this field, notably under the form of an amnesty,"
said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed for a "rapid resumption of functioning of
institutions" of Cambodia, whose main task he said is to prepare
for the May 1998 general elections.
</P>
<P>
"The international community cannot accept that the elections
go on in the conditions which would not respect the spirit of the
Paris accords" which call for a national reconciliation and
denounce violence, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the general elections call for the
establishment within the shortest time of a constitutional
council, a council of magistration, an electoral code, a law on
parties, the liberty of expression, security of persons, and an
equal access to the media by all parties.
</P>
<P>
He again called on the Phnom Penh government to let all the
parliament deputies, who quit Cambodia in July after Ranariddh was
ousted from power by Hun Sen, to return home with all security
guaranteed, so that the elections can be held "in the conditions
of liberty and incontestable balance."
</P>
<P>
He finally praised the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) for the mediation efforts it made among all the parties of
Cambodia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
