<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Said at Work on New Designs of Nuclear Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A private group claims that the
United States is hard at work on new designs of nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based Natural Resources Defense council says the
U.S. is working on some types of warheads including steps toward
redesigning the heart of the hydrogen bomb, its atomic trigger,
the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Council made the judgement based on an Energy Department
document declassified in June and plans to make it public
tomorrow, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The work focuses on the B-61 bomb for planes, the W-87 warhead
for MX missiles and the W-76 and W-88 warheads for Trident
missiles launched from submarines, the document was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Council says the work in some cases is meant to increase
the power and precision of the weapons and to strengthen them for
jobs like penetrating deep into the earth to knock out enemy
bunkers.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Department however insists that it is only
modernizing old designs with a goal of increasing the warheads's
life, safety and security while denying that it is making new
weapons or enhancing explosive power of nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
The Department which maintains the nation's nuclear arsenal for
the military, says its work adheres to the intent of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, but critics disagree with this,
the New york Times added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
