<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Prefers Bongo to Kabila in Congo Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- France today indirectly indicated
that it prefers Gabonese President Omar Bango to President
Laurent-Desire Kabila of the Democratic Republic of Congo in
mediating a settlement to the conflict in the Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
While describing as "normal" that the neighbor countries of
the Congo Republic is interested in looking for a solution to the
conflict in the country, French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves
Doutriaux said that France has always "firmly supported" the
mediation provided by Bongo and U.N. envoy Mohamed Sahnoun.
</P>
<P>
Kabila and President Pascal Lissouba reached an agreement today
upon the dispatch of an international force to Brazzaville "in a
brief delay."
</P>
<P>
The force could consist of soldiers from Angola, Central
African Republic, Chad, Rwanda, Burundi, the Democratic Republic
of Congo, and Uganda, according to Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been going on since June between the forces
supporting President Lissouba and Cobra militiamen supporting
former President Denis Sassou-NGuesso in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
The mediation provided by Bongo and Sahnoun has so far failed
to persuade the two conflicting sides to lay down their arms.
</P>
</TEXT>
