<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Warns Zimbabwe Against Deepening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- World Bank consultant Gloria
Mkombachoto today warned the Zimbabwean government against paying
lip service to the deepening economic crisis that threatens to
undermine the peace and tranquility prevailing in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said while the government had, through successive budget
statements, acknowledged the existence of some economic woes that
had afflicted the country since independence in 1980, it had
shown little commitment to finding a permanent solution to the
problems.
</P>
<P>
"These problems are known by everyone, especially the people
and companies that are affected compared to the policy makers,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"To this end, it is proposed that before these economic
problems translate into severe social and ultimately political
problems, let's not temper with the peace and tranquility that is
currently prevailing in this country," he told participants
attending a two-day post budget seminar that opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The comments came in the wake of the 1997/98 budget presented
to parliament last month, and described in some circles as
"standstill" or "non-event".
</P>
<P>
Among the main components of the budget were cuts in real
terms of allocations for some key social ministries as well as
the absence of clear strategies to promote investment and create
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Signs of economic stress among Zimbabwe's 12 million people
were beginning to show through strikes at unprecedented levels by
workers in both the public and private sectors, according to the
World Bank official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends to Establish a Peace-Building Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended the Security Council to establish a
peace-building support office to succeed the mandate of the United
Nations Observer mission in Liberia(UNOMIL).
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said with the
establishment of a democratically elected government in the
country, the principle objective of UNOMIL had now been achieved.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said that the mandate of UNOMIL would
expire on September 30 and the withdrawal of UNOMIL personnel was
already underway and should be substantially completed by that
date, leaving a small team to complete the usual liquidation and
closing process.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said the establishment of a peace-building
support office in Liberia could greatly assist the new government
on its efforts for reconciliation and reconstruction and
contribute to promoting peace and stability in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Gold Mine Closed as Gold Prices Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The fall in gold prices in the
world market has claimed its first victim in zimbabwe with the
closure of Rio Tinto Zimbabwe's (RTZ) Brompton Mine near Kadoma,
140 km south-west of Harare.
</P>
<P>
RTZ announced today that the company has not been able to
sustain profitable operations due to losses incurred in the first
half of this year, in which gold traded at an average 347 U.S.
Dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
"The recent fall in the gold price to levels well below this
figure has compounded the problems of the operation and in the
circumstances further losses cannot be maintained," said Frank
Webster, group personnel and public relations manager of the
mining conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
Gold prices have been falling since the beginning of the year
partly due to the disposal or threat thereof by central banks
which are making efforts to meet the criteria for entry into the
European Monetary Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Differences Are Main Barriers to Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Political differences are the
main barriers to the promotion of economic relations among member
nations of the South Asian Association of Regional Cooperation
(SAARC), Pakistani Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said today.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made the remarks while addressing a two-day seminar on
"South Asia' 97 -- Towards a Progressive Economic Union" held in
Pakistan's southern port city of Karachi, the official Associated
Press of Pakistan reported.
</P>
<P>
Referring particularly to the Indo-Pak relations, the minister
said that "if political relations warm up, the economic relations
will automatically improve."
</P>
<P>
Since its birth, SAARC has not made the desired progress due to
political differences among member countries like Pakistan and
India, he added.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the South Asian region, where inhabits one-fifth
of the population of the world, have been offered tremendous
opportunities to work together for mutual benefit by meeting the
demand of consumers, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He added that considerable progress has been made by the
economies of South Asian countries on their way towards a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
There was need for formation of a strong regional block in this
part of the world to avail maximum profits of inter-trade, Aziz
said.
</P>
<P>
"As a single country we would have limited exports, but as a
regional block we could enhance exports for our mutual benefit,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies Holding Oslo III Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Osama el-Baz, political advisor to
the Egyptian president, today denied reports on holding Oslo 3
talks with the participation of Israel, the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), Egypt and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Baz, who is leaving here for a few-day visit to Norway, said
that his visit to Oslo, the Norwegian capital, comes at the
invitation of the Norwegian Foreign Ministry to discuss bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
"Talks in Oslo will deal with the Mideast peace process
developments as well as the Egyptian and Norwegian role in the
peace drive," he added in his departure statement.
</P>
<P>
Baz said that he would not meet with any Palestinian or Israeli
official in Oslo, saying that press reports on Oslo III talks were
"bare of truth."
</P>
<P>
After 14 rounds of secret negotiations under the brokerage of
Norway, the Palestinians and Israelis reached a principled
agreement on Palestinian autonomy in Oslo in August 1993, a
historical breakthrough that gave the peace process new life.
</P>
<P>
The two sides formally signed the Interim Accord, known as the
Oslo II, in Washington in September.
</P>
<P>
Baz noted that four years passed since then but the peace
process is still stalled. "The U.S. and Egypt are exerting sincere
efforts but they are, however, hindered by the measures taken by
the Israeli government," he added.
</P>
<P>
Baz hoped that Israel would ease the closure of the
Palestinian self-rule territories and "fulfill its commitments
regarding the Palestinian Authority."
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the U.S. have been working to ease the economic
sanctions and overall closure Israel imposed on the Palestinians
following a double suicide bombing in a Jewish market in Jerusalem
on July 30 which killed 16 people.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu suspended a
resumption of talks with the PNA on so-called confidence building
measures after the bombing, which deepened a peace-making crisis
that was caused by Israel's launching of a Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First African Workshop on Environmental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The first ever African workshop
on environmental litigation opened here today in a bid to work
out means of protecting the environment and natural resources
using legal means.
</P>
<P>
The one-week workshop organised by Ugadan National
Environmental Management Authority (NEMA) and sponsored by the
United Nations Environmental Programme (UNEP) drew participants
from judicial officers from Kenya, South Africa, Uganda,
Mozambique, Tanzania and Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Opening the workshop, the attorney general and minister for
justice Bart Katureebe regretted that the subject of
environmental law although not very new in the legal field has
had little emphasis and attention in most African countries.
</P>
<P>
He therefore urged lawyers to prepare ground for creating
legal precedant which has all along been the preserve of natural
scientists.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for sensitisation of law enforcement
agencies of the existance of issues such as environmental crimes.
</P>
<P>
He also regretted that it is still amazing that a policeman on
the street or lawyer who has not been exposed to environmental
law will not appreciate the usefulness of issues such as
protection of wetlands and therefore find it very difficult to
arrest a suspect who has polluted a river and therefore take such
a person to police station or charge him for a criminal offence.
</P>
<P>
The deputy executive director of NEMA Henry Aryamanya Mugisha
streesed the need in his speech for members of the legal
profession to acquaint themselves with the new thinking of
environmental law.
</P>
<P>
He said this will reduce the stress on the judicial system,
which is already overburdened with cases which would otherwise be
settled before the conflicts occur. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0016 </DOCNO>
