<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Regional Labour Seminar Opens in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A five-day African regional
labour administration seminar started here today, discussing
possible areas of labour harmonisation, cooperation and
integration.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which was organised by the African Regional
Labour Administration Centre (ARLAC), seeks to sensitise the
participants to the implications of emerging regional and
sub-regional cooperation for national labour policy formulations
and implementation.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 delegates from 20 English-speaking countries
attended the seminar.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Tayo Fashoyin, director of the ARLAC,
urged African governments to consider harmonising their labour
regulations, industrial relations and movement of workers across
national boundaries to create a common market for the continent.
</P>
<P>
He said the harmonisation of such regulations would provide
Africa with a common framework to achieve a measure of
flexibility in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Of the three main areas that deserve harmonisation, a policy
on the movement of workers has long been overdue despite the fact
that it has posed the greatest challenge to economic integration,
said Fashoyin.
</P>
<P>
He added that the process of articulating a sub-regional
approach to social regulations is a "commendable" one which may
serve as a useful framework for social and economic regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
