<HEADLINE> Britain to Help Evacuate Montserrat Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) --- The British government has
expressed its readiness to help evacuate the remaining residents
of the Carribbean island of Montserrat as experts warned that a
massive volcanic eruption was approaching.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the British Foreign Office and the Overseas
Development Office were reportedly holding urgent talks on the
worsening situation in the island, which has been repeatedly
attacked by a series of volcanic eruptions.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman said here today: "With all the smoke
and ash from the volcano, it's impossible to fly."
</P>
<P>
He noted that a ferry service to neighboring islands such as
Antigua was another option for those residents wishing to leave
Montserrat.
</P>
<P>
On the islanders' options of possible final destinations, he
said: "Not everyone wants to go to the UK. Some have gone to the
U.S. where there is a big Montserrat community and others may want
to go to neighboring islands on a temporary basis."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Britain's International Development Minister George
Foulkes said earlier today that the possibility of a "massive,
cataclysmic-intensive eruption" of the volcano could not be ruled
out.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past 24 hours the volcano has become much more
dangerous. As a result we have agreed to this voluntary partial
evacuation of anyone who wants to leave in the wake of this
information," Foulkes said.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the Montserrat Volcano Observatory had warned the
consequences of a possible massive eruption would be disastrous
and anywhere on the island could be significantly threatened.
</P>
<P>
The island's population is sharply down to less than half the
11,000 residents living there before the volcano became active
again in July 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
