<HEADLINE> HSBC Values Highly Relationship with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) - HSBC's relationship with China is
one of the most important ones it has in the world, claimed John
Bond, the chief executive of HSBC Group.
</P>
<P>
Bond made the remarks during an exclusive interview with Xinhua
recently, saying that "it is a very long relationship which we
value highly".
</P>
<P>
HSBC Holding's Plc is one of the largest banking and financial
services organizations in the world. Its international network
comprised more than 5,000 offices in 78 countries.
</P>
<P>
The Group's total assets at 30 June 1997 were 275 billion pounds
(440 billion US dollars) and increased of 39 billion pounds (52.4
billion US dollars), or 16% since year-end 1996.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent trip to Hongkong, where he chaired a
press conference on Hongkong Bank 1997 Interim Results, Bond said:
"We are delighted with the way the unification has been gone so
smoothly.... the mood there was extremely good."
</P>
<P>
"People are very confident and it is just what Chinese leaders
have always said 'business as usual' and this is what exactly HSBC
expected," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the future relationship with China, Bond said: "We
have a very clear strategy in China; we want to develop our
business there in every way that we can, but clearly in a way that
matches China's economic aspirations."
</P>
<P>
Bond was very pleased that HSBC has been one of the first
foreign banks that have been granted licence to deal RMB in
Shanghai since last March.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on China's monetary and financial policy, Bond said
China is doing RMB business "extremely well"; it is taking a "step
by step" policy which is a "right way to go".
</P>
<P>
Bond stressed : "We understand the policies China adopted,"
saying that "You should walk before you can run."
</P>
<P>
Expressing HSBC's confidence in China's economy, Bond told
Xinhua that "HSBC is going to hold a board meeting in Beijing later
next month, so board members can see China's magnitude of the
achievements brought about by the economic reform policy since
1978."  
</P>
</TEXT>
