<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Blames Turkey for Failed Talks on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Greece today accused Turkey of
being responsible for the failure of the second round of direct
talks between Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash which took place in Switzerland last
week.
</P>
<P>
In an interview in the Athens daily, The News, Greece's Foreign
Undersecretary Yannos Kranidiotis said that the breakdown of the
U.N.-sponsored direct talks in Switzerland between the two leaders
was due not only to Denktash's stance but to the Turkish
government.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Cypriot government had come to the
negotiating table in a "constructive mood," but on the contrary,
the Turkish side participated in the talks with the aim of
stalling the process of Cyprus' accession to the European Union
(EU) as well as the installation of the Russian-made S-300
missiles in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that both Cyprus and Greece, with their consistent
stance, have already made the right impression," he said, adding
that "it is up to the international community to attribute the
blame for the deadlock to the Turkish side and not to equate the
victimizer with the victim."
</P>
<P>
As for the text presented at the talks by U.N. mediator Diego
Cordovez, He said that although the text contained "several weak
points," it nevertheless confirmed the need for the unified and
indivisible sovereignty of the Cypriot Federation.
</P>
<P>
He described this as "a positive and significant developments"
in favor of Greece's positions and policy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kranidiotis also mentioned the role to be played by
U.S. presidential envoy on the Cyprus problem Richard Holbrooke,
saying that the envoy's role should be "supplementary" to that of
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"We expect Mr. Holbrooke to exercise his influence on the
Turkish side so that it cooperates in the international effort to
solve the Cyprus issue based on international principles," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts believe that the crucial period for the
Cyprus problem will be 1998 following the presidential elections
in Cyprus and the beginning of negotiations for Cyprus's accession
to the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
