<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Finds Link Between Violent Videos, Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A UK Home Office-commissioned
research is expected to establish the first official causal link
between crime and screen violence, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled The Effectiveness of Video Violence on
Young Offenders, to be published in October, is to suggest that
aggressive people are more likely to commit violent acts more
frequently after watching videos than non-aggressive youngsters.
</P>
<P>
The two-year study, which used a sample of 120 aged 15-21
youths, including young offenders, compared the reaction of normal
youths watching video nasties with that of violent and non-violent
offenders.
</P>
<P>
The Study is to show that violent offenders and non-offenders
react differently to violent videos and films, with the former
remembering more details of brutal acts in the movies and
identifying more closely with the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the study will put pressure on the British
government to tighten censorship rules for those believed to be
most easily swayed by depictions of violence in videos.
</P>
<P>
The Home Secretary Jack Straw is also expected to tighten
regulations covering the sale,distribution and screening of films
to make it harder for young people to watch violent movies.
</P>
<P>
Young offenders in institutions could be banned from watching
violent videos, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0029 </DOCNO>
