<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has set aside 40 million
U.S. dollars for the purchase of medicines and medical supplies
from Egypt after the renewal of oil-for-food deal, an Egyptian
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian delegation will visit Baghdad soon to find out
which types of medicines Iraq needs the most, Director of the
state-owned Pharmaceutical Holding Company Galal Ghorab was quoted
by the Egyptian MENA news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, which estimates its medicine needs at 240 million dollars
for this year, will announce an international bid by next week for
the purchase of medicines, he added.
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council agreed in June to extend the
oil-for-food agreement allowing Iraq to sell 2 billion dollars in
oil for another six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
During the first stage of the agreement which took effect last
December, Egypt, which is the leading Arab country to call for an
early lift of the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after it's 1990
invasion of Kuwait, became the largest official supplier of aid to
Iraq among the Arab countries. 
</P>
