<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Abacha Visits Cote d'Ivoire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state General
Sani Abacha this morning paid a working visit to Cote d'Ivoire
and had closed-door talks with his Ivorian counterpart President
Henri Konan Bedie.
</P>
<P>
According to the British Broadcast Corporation, the visit was
shorter than originally said 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Abacha arrived in the capital Abidjan at around 9:30 a.m. and
left before lunch time, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The whole meeting was totally discreet as the two leaders
talked without the presence of any interpreter.
</P>
<P>
However, since both countries are working together closely in
the ECOWAS Committee of Four on Sierra Leone, observers here
believe how to restore that country's civilian government toppled
in the May 25 coup must have been the focus of their discussions.
</P>
<P>
The committee, made up of Nigeria, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire and
Guinea, is set up by the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) to seek ways to reverse the coup. It has
announced a combination of three measures to settle the issue,
namely, dialogue, sanctions and use of force.
</P>
<P>
To date, the talks between the committee and representatives
of the junta in Sierra Leone has collapsed after the military
regime said it would stay in power until the year 2001. Sanctions
against the junta has since been tightened.
</P>
<P>
The observers noted that Nigeria might be the only member of
the committee keen on military intervention while the other three
countries, particularly Ghana and Cote d'Ivoire, have been urging
caution.
</P>
<P>
They have said everything possible should be done to avoid the
use of force.
</P>
<P>
Cote d'Ivoire is the last country in the committee which
Abacha, the current ECOWAS chairman, has paid a brief visit since
the coup took place in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the Nigerian leader is under some pressure in
dealing with the Sierra Leonean crisis, especially when the
ECOWAS summit is to be held next week.
</P>
<P>
Most observers believe the issue of Sierra Leone will be high
on the agenda of the coming summit of heads of state and
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
