<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Detention of Rwandan Genocide Suspects Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) in Arusha, Northern
Tanzaniaa, has extended the detention for another 30 days of four
Rwandan genocide suspects to allow more time for the prosecution
to finalize its investigation.
</P>
<P>
Judge Laity Kama, President of the tribunal, granted the
extension today following the prosecutor's request that the
detention of the four be extended because of the complexity of
the investigations, an ICTR press statement released today said.
</P>
<P>
Granting the request, Judge Kama reminded the prosecution to
ensure that it presents the indictments of the accused as soon as
possible because the rules provide that the period of detention
shall not exceed 90 days, at the end of which, in the event the
indictments are not confirmed, the suspects shall be released.
</P>
<P>
The four suspects are George Ruggiu, a Belgian journalist who
worked with Radio Television Libre des Mille Collines, Aloys
Ntabakuze, a former commander of the para commando battalion of
the Rwandan army, Sylvain Nsabimana, a former prefect of Butare,
and Gratien Kabiligi, a former colonel in the general staff of
the Rwandan army until July 1994.
</P>
<P>
They were arrested in Nairobi, Kenya, exactly a month ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
