<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Allows Iranians to Visit Its Holy Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
today issued orders to allow Iranian citizens to visit the holy
sites in Iraq as from September 4, the first time since the
beginning of the eight-year war between the two countries in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at a joint meeting today of the Iraqi
Revolutionary Command Council and the ruling Arab Ba'ath Socialist
Party under the chairmanship of the president.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi news agency today quoted an official spokesman as
saying that the decision conforms to humanitarian principles in
the president's speech on August 8, expressing the good will of
Iraq towards the Iranian people.
</P>
<P>
In the address, Saddam called upon Iran to pursue a policy of
cooperation, stabilization of relations and development of
bilateral ties, on the basis mutual respect and non-interference
in each other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed the hope that the Iranian visitors will
abide by the related regulations and instructions, and to foil any
attempt of undermining this initiative.
</P>
<P>
He described the Iraqi initiative as constituting a linkage and
good omen for the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has the tombs of Imam Ali Bin Abu Talib, Imam Al Hussein,
and several other holy sites to the Shiite Muslims, who make up
the majority of the Iranian people.
</P>
<P>
One of the most serious residues of this war is the issue of
prisoners of war and those missing-in-action. It constitutes the
prime obstacle in the face of normalization of diplomatic and
political relations between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
