<HEADLINE> CPDM Won Re-run of Legislative Elections in Three </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Camerounian supreme court
has in Yaounde today officially proclaimed the final results of
the re-run of the legislative elections in Cameroun on August 3
with the CPDM winning all the seven seats in three
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 12 political parties took part in the re-run of the
legislative elections in the Mayo Banyo division of Adamaoua
province, Mayo Rey division of the North province and the Nde
division of the West province.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Cameroun People's Democratic Movement (CPDM) has
obtained an absolute mojority in the three constituencies winning
all the seven seats as follows: two seats in the Mayo Banyo
division, two seats in the Nde division and three seats in the
Mayo Rey division.
</P>
<P>
The supreme court sitting as the constitutional council also
rejected the petitions sent in by the two major opposition
parties: the Social Democratic Front (SDF) and the National Union
for Democracy and Progess (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The two parties called for the cancellation of the re-run of
the legislative elections in the Nde and Mayo banyo divisions
respectively due to irregularities during the elections.
</P>
<P>
The supreme court examined the petitions and rejected the
petitions for lacking of evidence.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun's legislative elections were held on May 17
throughout the territory with some 3.7 million voters casting
their votes. About 1000 representatives of 45 political parties
competed for the 180 seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
With the proclamation of the results, the 180 seats in
parliament have been shared by seven political parties.
</P>
<P>
It is certain that only two political parties - the CPDM and
the SDF are having parliamentarian groups in the current
legislature, the UNDP is not going to have a parliamentarian
group since it is two seats short of the minimum 15. 
</P>
