<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interests Money Go to Both Parties in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A new report by a campaign
reform advocacy group says that in the first half of this year,
the insurance and tobacco industries were the top soft-money
donors to the Republican Party in the United States, while labor
unions and lawyers contributed the most to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
The non-partisan organization Common Cause in a study released
today reports that the Republicans raised a record-setting 23.1
million dollars during the first six months of this year. The
Democrats came in at half that amount with 11.1 million dollars in
contributions.
</P>
<P>
The report says the insurance industry gave about 1.7 million
dollars to the Republicans in the period, just ahead of
contributions from the tobacco interests totaling nearly 1.6
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the Democratic side, unions contributed 934,454 dollars,
while lawyers and lobbyists contributed 817,600 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The hard-to-trace soft money contributions were made to the
political parties by subsidiaries or top executives in the
respective industries. The soft-money donations, made directly to
the parties for party building efforts, often go one way or
another to the individual campaigns in a system that often avoids
detection.
</P>
<P>
There has been increased momentum urging to ban the practice,
though with no success so far.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the top individual soft-money donors
for the Republicans were Mr. and Mrs. Richard DeVos of the Amway
Corp. at 1 million dollars; Philip Morris Co. at 653,715 dollars;
and RJR Nabisco/RJ Reynold's Tobacco at 340,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report says the top individual soft-money donors for the
Democrats were Connell Rice &AMP; Sugar Co. at 200,000 dollars;
Slim-Fast Foods Co. /Thompson Medical Co. at 200,000 dollars; and
the Communication Workers of America at 195,500 dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
