<HEADLINE> Japan Grants Zambia 5.6 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government will
provide Zambia with 7.3 billion Kwacha (about 5.6 million U.S.
Dollars) to improve water supply surrounding the capital city of
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Under the exchange of notes signed here today, the money will
cover the third and fourth phases of the water supply project in
George Complex.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Finance Minister Ronald Penza who signed the exchange
of notes said that after the completion of phase one and two,
there is a general decrease of water-borne diseases in the area
and 60,000 people of George compound have access to adequate safe
water supply.
</P>
<P>
Penza told Japanese ambassador to Zambia Yoshihiro Nakamura
that the Zambian government's aim is to increase access to safe
and clean water supply in urban areas by 100 percent in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese ambassador who signed the notes said that the
grant will be used for the construction of a pipeline network,
water distribution facilities as well as two boreholes and water
tanks.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government is willing to assist the Zambian
people when self-help efforts are positively evident in any
project, Nakamura said. 
