<HEADLINE> Turkish President Criticized for Signing New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's pro-Islamic Welfare
Party (RP) today criticized President Suleyman Demirel for signing
a controversy education reform bill.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in the Parliament, the Deputy
Chairman of RP's Parliamentary Group Salih Kapusuz, accused
Demirel of lacking careful consideration before signing it.
</P>
<P>
Demirel signed the eight-year compulsory education refrom bill
into law last Sunday after the Parliament passed the bill
following a heated debate.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Demirel took the quick action in
order to show his firm support for the Mesut Yilmaz government
and other secularists.
</P>
<P>
Kapusuz said that Cankaya (the presidential palace) made a
mistake by signing the Education Ministry-proposed bill, which
caused great anger among the RP and its supporters.
</P>
<P>
"The president should have shown the same sensitivity to this
bill that he showed to other bills," he added.
</P>
<P>
The eight-year compulsory education reform bill was passed in
the Parliament last Saturday by 277 to 242, marking an initial
victory of the secularist establishment.
</P>
<P>
On the role played by Yilamz over the education reform bill
issue, Kapusuz claimed that the prime minister is adopting a
hostile attitude toward the religious people.
</P>
<P>
He accused the ruling Motherland Party chairman of engaging
in "separatism" in pushing forward his education reform program.
</P>
<P>
The RP parliamentary group leader vowed that RP will apply to
the Constitutional Court, Turkey's supreme judicial organ, to
have the new law annulled.
</P>
<P>
A large number of religious schools have to be closed in
accordance with the new law, which is believed to be a fresh blow
to the conservative Islamists following the forced resigning of
the pro-Islamic Necmettin Erbakan administration in June.
</P>
<P>
Students, if they like, have to finish their eight years
of compulsory education before they enter religious schools where
the Koranic lessons are given.
</P>
<P>
The Yilamz government has repeatedly stated that this
education reform was extremely important for the continuation of
Turkey's democracy and secularist system, saying it would prevent
fundamentalists from expanding in the secular republic.
</P>
<P>
However, RP and its leader Erbakan were greately angered by the
adoption of the controversial education reform bill, threatening
that the party would try every means to block the implementation
of the new law.
</P>
<P>
The military, who calls itself a defender of Turkey's
secularism and democracy, has shown resolute support to Yilmaz
and his government's efforts for the passage of the key bill in
the Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
