<HEADLINE> Northern Iraq in Disorder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The northern Iraqi province of
Sulaymaniyah is in a state of disorder resulted from the
activities of various Kurdish parties in the region, local
newspapers and radio stations reported today.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) has arrested 700
citizens for the past week in the province on charges of
collaborating with Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), which is
allied with President Saddam Hussein's army.
</P>
<P>
The Sulaymaniyah province is the last stronghold of the PUK in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PUK and KDP, the two main Kurdish parties in effective
control of northern Iraq, have clashed for about three years,
largely over duties leveled on oil trucked across the border with
Turkey in violation of U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. The duties are the main source of income
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the arrest campaign is still going
on today.
</P>
<P>
Also in the province, a number of boys aging between 7 and 10
years have recently been abducted by elements belonging to the
Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which has been fighting a
13-year-old separatist war in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The boys will allegedly be trained militarily and be used
in the fighting against Turkish troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
