<HEADLINE> Northern Cyprus Condemns Murder of Turkish Cypriot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot Leader Rauf
Denktash today condemned the killing of a Turkish Cypriot on the
Greek Cypriot side of the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Cihan Necip Hakyemez, a 38-year-old Turkish Cypriot, was shot
and killed by a masked Greek Cypriot as he was riding a
motorcycle in Limassol, a mixed town of both Greek and Turkish
Cypriots, last Saturday, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Denktash, who has just returned from the failed peace talks
with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides in Switzerland last Week,
maintained that Hakyemez was assassinated by a secret armed Greek
Cypriot gang.
</P>
<P>
"It was also like this in the old times. They would shoot down
everyone they thought was a spy in the mixed towns," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, a small island state in the eastern Mediterranean, has
remained divided since 1974 when Turkey invaded and took over the
northern third of its in the wake of a pro-Athens coup by Greek
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side unilaterally declared the setting up
of the so-called "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983,
which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been making efforts for years in a bid
to bring a peace solution to the rival Turkish and Greek Cypriot
communities, but no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Denktash and Clerides held their second round of
peace negotiations in the Swiss town of Montreux under the
U.N. mediation, but the talks ended in deadlock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
