<HEADLINE> Palestine: Egyptian Role Important for Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nabil Shaath, minister of planning
and international cooperation at the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) said today the Egyptian mediation role is vital
for moving the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
here, Shaath hailed Egypt as "the main pillar for a fair peaceful
solution and restoration of the Palestinian rights."
</P>
<P>
Implementing main terms of reference of the peace process and
the relevant accords signed by parties concerned mark the axis of
Egyptian endeavors, said Shaath.
</P>
<P>
The Moussa-Shaath meeting was held in light of efforts exerted
to stem the deterioration of the peace process and ease the
Israeli-clamped economic siege of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Moussa said by no
means should the terms of reference of the peace process,
including the land-for-peace principle, be given up.
</P>
<P>
"Once such terms are forsaken there is no way to ensure the
implementation of subsequent agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shaath said Israel is demolishing peace. "Its policies that
involve siege on Palestinians, starving them out, razing their
homes, and persisting with settlement building -- all pose as the
real danger jeopardizing peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Freezing Palestinian funds and denying Palestinian workers
access to their workplaces stand as manifestations for a war of
starvation and economic siege," Shaath pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-Palestinian coordination is the most efficient way to
save the peace process, he said, asserting that the PNA honors its
security commitments stipulated in the accords signed with Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the PNA rejects the Israeli-imposed demands
to arrest 125 Palestinians on the pretext of fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Israel is carrying out a mass punishment for something
Palestinians have nothing to do with," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has introduced tough security measures against
Palestinians and demanded the PNA to round up suspects since the
double bombings in a Jerusalem market that killed 14 Israeli
civilians on July 30.
</P>
<P>
Shaath said that he discussed with Moussa the future of the
peace process in light of the prospective visit by U.S. Secretary
of State Medeleine Albright which he regards as an important one
highly evaluated by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the U.S. have been working to ease the economic
sanctions and overall closure Israel imposed on the Palestinians
following the bombings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
