<HEADLINE> Technical Committee on Kuwait POWs Meets, No Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A technical sub-committee
including members from Kuwait, Iraq and nations of the 1991 Gulf
War held their 25th monthly meeting on Kuwaiti POWs today on the
Kuwaiti-Iraqi borders, but no results were achieved.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by representatives from Kuwait,
Iraq, Saudi Arabia, the United States, Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
Previous meetings had also ended in failure due to differences
on the Prisoners of War issue from both Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait claimed that more than 600 Kuwaitis and third country
nationals were brought to Iraq at the end of the Gulf War in 1991
and have been detained in Iraqi jails while Baghdad denied.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Kuwaiti National Committee for Missing
and POWs Affairs said that the committee members discussed the
"proposed agenda" and decided to hold the 26th meeting on the
Iraqi part of the Kuwait-Iraqi border on September 24, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the previous meetings, Iraq acknowledged taking along with
withdrawing troops some POWs to Iraq, but saying it possessed no
fresh knowledge of their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad alleged that a number of the Kuwait POWs had gone
missing during a popular uprising that broke out in southern
Iraq following the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The POWs' issue has been one of the key factors hindering
any improvement of relations between Kuwait and Iraq within
the context of an Arabic reconciliation drive in which Kuwait
started to restore normal ties this year with countries such
as Jordan, Sudan and Yemen who sided with Iraq during the
war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students Stage Demonstration in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- At least 30 students were
arrested by the military authorities and two were feared being
killed in a protest demonstration today in Freetown, the capital
of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, the State Radio,
which is controlled by the junta in power, has not released any
concrete figures, but a spokesman of the junta admitted that the
military had taken some measures to "contain" the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also accused the students of wounding soldiers
who were heavily armed on security mission.
</P>
<P>
"The students are armed with AK47s we have too", he said,
adding that the soldiers had to take the students away.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces Revolutionary Council, the current highest
governing body of Sierra Leone, refused Sunday to grant
permission for the demonstration proposed for today, threatening
to clamp down.
</P>
<P>
But one of the leaders behind today's students' protest denied
the demonstration posed any threat to the situation of the
country charged by the army, saying that it was a peaceful
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
He said the students were only trying to stop blood shedding
in the country and did not prepare to take arms.
</P>
<P>
As the next step, the organizers of the demonstration will
call on all Sierra Leoneans to stay in house instead of going out
to work.
</P>
<P>
In Bo, the second largest city of Sierra Leone, students
echoed their colleagues in Freetown and also went out to the
streets for demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The students called on the military junta to go and demanded
the return of ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
After marching for a while, they came face to face with the
heavily armed soldiers and police, and sat down in the street
peacefully, only to be dispersed quickly.
</P>
<P>
The students later re-grouped in another part of the town and
were once again chased away by the combined security forces.
</P>
<P>
No clashes were reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sierra Leoneans on exile in neighboring Guinea were
also meeting at a gathering today to call for the restoration of
Kabbha.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration in front of the Sierra Leonean embassy in
Conakry, capital of Guinea, went on peacefully.
</P>
<P>
While the demonstrators were marching around the embassy,
another demonstration organized by a group calling itself as the
Movement for the Restoration of Democracy was also happening
right in the embassy compound.
</P>
<P>
This group called for the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) to help reinstate Kabbah's government by any
means necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
