<HEADLINE> Germany Provides Vessels to Check Drug Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Germany will provide three
vessels to Pakistan for doing coast-guard duty to check drug
smuggling, visiting German Deputy Defense Minister Bernd Wilz said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Pakistan have also agreed to enhance bilateral
cooperation in the areas of common interests, Wilz told a news
conference held here at the Germany Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, he said, would assist each other for
education and training of their armed forces personnel.
</P>
<P>
Terming his talks with Pakistani officials "very fruitful",
Wilz said his visit was aimed at "getting and giving information
about the defense needs".
</P>
<P>
He said he held wide-ranging talks with Pakistani officials,
covering Kashmir and Afghanistan and expressed appreciation over
Pakistan's handling of the regional affairs for maintaining peace.
</P>
<P>
German was prepared to extend possible support to India and
Pakistan for disarmament, arms control and taking confidence
building measures, Wilz said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about his country's stand on the Kashmir issue, the
German minister said "we appreciate the talks held recently"
between Pakistan and India, adding this is the right way to settle
the problem.
</P>
<P>
On the Afghan issue, Wilz said Pakistan is handling the Afghan
issue very well", particularly Pakistan's role providing
assistance to Afghan refugees is commendable.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, sincerely desires to have peace in
Afghanistan and is making all possible efforts for this purpose.
</P>
</TEXT>
