<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Communities Urged to Settle Their Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Special Envoy for
Cyprus, Sir David Hannay has urged the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities to make a contribution toward a settlement to the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting in an interview with London Greek Radio
on the two rounds of U.N.-led direct talks between the Greek
and Turkish sides, aimed at reaching a comprehensive solution to
the protracted Cyprus problem, according to Cyprus News Agency
today.
</P>
<P>
The second round of talks, ended in failure last Friday
in Glion-sur-Montreux, Switzerland, followed the first round of
face-to-face talks, held in Troutbeck, near New York from July
9 to 12.
</P>
<P>
Hannay told the radio that the two rounds of direct talks
were not put to the best possible use, but said a work
program will go ahead this autumn as neither President Glafcos
Clerides nor Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash had a problem
with this.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process is now going to move into a new gear
with the working by the U.N., in consultation with the two
parties, on the actual legal texts that will be needed for a
settlement," the British envoy added, noting they will cover
issues such as a draft constitution, territorial adjustments,
arrangements for security matters, refugees and compensation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that negotiations on these texts will
begin in March 1998, after the presidential elections in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that both Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot leader
Denktash have an important role to play in efforts for a solution,
but said "they have got to be satisfied through the process of
negotiations that their fundamental needs and requirements are
being taken account of as those of the other side."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkey sent troops and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been continuing
their efforts to reunite this island nation as a bi-communal,
bi-zonal federation despite repeated failure in peace talks for
past 23 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
