<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Roman-Jewish Battle Site Excavated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Evidence of the harrowing
battle for Yodfat in 67 B.C. during the great revolt against
the Roman has been uncovered in a current archeological dig, The
Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
On the painted floor of a luxurious mansion in Galilee region
in northern Israel, the excavators found the remains of a human
surrounded by arrowheads, vivid testimony to the last moments
after the Roman army broke into the city it had besieged for 47
days.
</P>
<P>
The remains of some 30 other victims, evidently reburied by
returning Jews years after the city's destruction, were found at
the bottom of a cistern which had been converted into a mass
grave.
</P>
<P>
The mansion, according to archeologist Motti Aviam of the
Antiquities Authority, contains exceptionally well preserved wall
murals similar to - perhaps superior to - those found from the
period in Massada and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
An unusual feature of the building was that the floor of the
central room in which the murals were located was also painted
in geometric design, apparently indicating that the building's
occupants walked there barefoot. It was in this room that the
body and arrowheads were found.
</P>
<P>
Yodfat was the first sizable city captured by the Romans in
their march on Jerusalem. It was the headquarters of Josephus,
who had been dispatched to the Galilee by the leaders of the
revolt in Jerusalem to organize the defenses in the north.
</P>
<P>
He survived the battle to become the great historian of the
period. It is from his own works that the story of the
battle for Yodfat became known.
</P>
<P>
The excavations at Yodat, now in their sixth season, are
being conducted by Aviam and Professor William Scott Green of the
University of Rochester in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
