<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects Breakthrough in State Sector Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China is expecting a major
breakthrough in reform of state-owned enterprises as it opens its
arms wider to the shareholding system.
</P>
<P>
Although the shareholding practice currently is being piloted
in only a few large- and medium-sized firms, it will be spread and
will lead to fundamental changes in the nation's state sector,
according to sources at the State Commission for Restructuring the
Economy (SCRE).
</P>
<P>
Economists say that China can count on a boom period for
shareholding, since a few Chinese provinces, including
southeastern Jiangsu and Anhui, and the northern Hebei Province,
have charted their timetables for transforming the state sector.
</P>
<P>
Since China launched the shareholding plan in the early 1980s,
the practice has been successful. But it also met with opposition
and some critics labeled it privatization.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the number of shareholder firms which evolved from
former state ventures, large- and medium-sized ones in particular,
has hovered around 9,000 since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Tensions eased recently when the state leaders clearly defined
shareholding as a good way to achieve public ownership, and an
enterprise system which may be taken in either a capitalist or a
socialist country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, in a speech at the Party School
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) in
May, called for bolder moves to be taken in economic reform.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China is still in the primary stage of
socialism and the reform drive should be conducive to boosting
the economy, increasing overall national strength, and improving
people's living standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects Breakthrough in State Sector Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese economists have envisioned a rosy future for the once
inert state sector, saying the state enterprises will become more
vigorous and competitive since shareholding may wipe away some
deep-rooted stumbling blocks to high economic efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the shareholding system has displayed its worth in
past experiments. According to managers of the pilot enterprises,
the shareholding practice had an immediate positive effect on
economic efficiency and reducing the asset-to-liability ratio of
the transformed enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"It also liberated the pilot state ventures from the
administrative influence, encouraged them to be market-oriented
and facilitated the establishment of a modern enterprise system in
response to a market economy," a company official said.
</P>
<P>
Fundamental changes also took place in those transformed state
enterprises since their assets had clear and various ownerships,
instead of sole state ownership.
</P>
<P>
The firms are also characterized by democratic management: the
board of directors, board of supervisors, and the general managers
assume their own responsibilities, compared with the past practice
of having everything decided by the government.
</P>
<P>
The shareholding firms will also operate more easily, as they
may raise the much-needed funds on the capital market. This makes
them more publicly-owned than ever, since it will be common for
the individuals to have a stake in the enterprises, with the state
holding a dominant percent of shares.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a salient feature of the newly-defined public
ownership in the future," said an economist.
</P>
<P>
But the government is aiming higher. Transforming state
ventures into shareholding firms has to be standardized in line
with the Corporate Law, said officials of the SCRE.
</P>
<P>
The board of directors, supervisors, and the shareholders
shouldn't be just figureheads, they must play an active role in
managing the transformed businesses, they stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
