<HEADLINE> OAU Chairman: Peace in Congo (B) Still Hopeful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe said
today hopes for a peaceful resolution of the conflict in Congo
Brazzaville have not faltered despite the violation of a
cease-fire agreement reached by the warring parties on July 13.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean President who doubles as Chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), and Congolese Foreign
Minister Destin Alsene Tsaty-Boungou both said peace is necessary
to ensure development.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who is leading the peace initiative for Congo (B),
said here, "we want to see the Republic of Congo develop in a
peaceful way."
</P>
<P>
Interviewed today after delivering a message to Mugabe from
President Pascal Lissouba, Tsaty-Boungou also said it was hoped
Congo (B) would have a government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese foreign minister said, "we would like to have a
government of national unity with members from the majority and
the Opposition."
</P>
<P>
A cease-fire agreement has been violated with troops
exchanging sporadic gunfire and mortar bombs.
</P>
<P>
Former Congolese strong man Denis Sassou-Nguesso last month
rejected a draft plan for peace between his militia and forces
loyal to Lissouba.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 5,000 people have been killed on weeks of fighting that
broke out in June when the government sought to disarm
Sassou-Nguesso's militia, ahead of the postponed presidential
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
