<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earliest Chinese Characters Found in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists have discovered
what they believe are the oldest Chinese characters ever written
in the country inscribed on oracle bones dating back some 4,000
years, according to the People's Daily today.
</P>
<P>
The two inscriptions were written nearly a millennium earlier
than the famous inscriptions on tortoise shells and ox bones that
were found in the Yin Ruins, the site of the capital city of the
late Shang Dynasty (16-11th Century BC), the experts said.
</P>
<P>
The newly-found inscriptions were found on two pieces of oracle
bones in the bottom of a large sacrificial pit, from which 356
pieces of pottery, stone, shell and bone ware were unearthed in
Huantai County, in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Though they have not deciphered all the characters, the experts
are confident that the two inscriptions are from the same origin.
</P>
<P>
From a site nearby, bronzeware bearing inscriptions which date
to the Shang Dynasty have also been found. Experts cited these as
the oldest inscriptions ever found on bronzeware,
</P>
<P>
The experts dated the inscriptions on oracles bones back to the
Longshan culture, which was after local Dawenkou culture, which is
renowned for its matriarchal society, in which the male sex is
worshiped.
</P>
<P>
In the Dawenkou society, according to the newspaper, women
worshiped the male reproductive organ, as evidenced in a recent
find at which a tortoise head was laid on the breast of a woman in
a tomb from some 6,000 years ago. The tomb was located in the
Lizhai archaeological site, which is two kilometers from the site
where the ancient oracle bone inscriptions were discovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
