<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Reactor Project Launched in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A ground-breaking ceremony was
held today in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
marking the start of a landmark nuclear reactor construction
project which was agreed upon by the DPRK and the U.S. in Geneva
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony began at 14:00 local time as scheduled at Kumbo in
the DPRK's eastern coastal province of South Hamkyong.
</P>
<P>
Under the Geneva Agreement signed between the U.S. and the DPRK
in October, 1994, an international consortium, the Korean
Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO), is to build two
1,000-megawatt light-water reactors there in return for DPRK's
promise to freeze its nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
Director of the DPRK's General Bureau of Atomic Energy Ri
Je-son and Ho Jong, a senior official of the Foreign Ministry,
attended today's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony signaled the full-scale launch of the Geneva
Agreement, Ho Jong said, adding that there was a long way to go to
finally fulfil the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the ceremony was an 81-member KEDO delegation,
which included government representatives from KEDO's three
executive nations: South Korea, Japan and the U.S., and officials
from the KEDO secretariat.
</P>
<P>
KEDO Executive Director Paul Cleveland, also the Washington
representative, conveyed a message from U.S. President Bill
Clinton, who promised that his country would do its best to help
make the goals of the 1994 Geneva Agreement a reality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
