<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crackdown on Illegal Commissions for Pharmaceuticals Strengthened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A national crackdown on both
soliciting and offering illegal kickbacks for pharmaceuticals has
yielded initial results.
</P>
<P>
The State Council decided to launch a major crackdown in May of
last year to bring an end to rampant nationwide unlawful
activities which disrupted market order, corrupted medical
professionals, sparked rising prices for pharmaceuticals and
supported the production of substandard or counterfeit
pharmaceutical products.
</P>
<P>
Since then, over 4,400 cases involving the illegal kickbacks
were reported to departments concerned, of which over 2,700 have
been dealt with, and 2,019 have been concluded, according to a
press conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
Of the cases, 664 are considered serious, since they either
involve individuals each giving or receiving illegal commissions
worth over 10,000 yuan (1,204.8 US dollars), or units each giving
or receiving kickbacks of over 100,000 yuan, according to
information from the press conference jointly held by several
central government departments.
</P>
<P>
It was also announced that reporters should give national media
exposure to 15 extremely serious cases.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence of their illegal acts, several pharmaceutical
companies, department stores, and hospitals were fined, five
persons were imprisoned for terms ranging six to 14 years, and
three others received administrative warnings.
</P>
<P>
In the most serious case, Du Yunyun, a chief pharmacist of a
railway hospital in Beijing, was sentenced to 14 years
imprisonment for receiving commissions of over 170,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Over 20,000 cases of producing fake or substandard medicine,
and over 9,000 unauthorized medicine dealers were punished,
according to the press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
