<HEADLINE> Hard Times for Russia's Aviation Industry are Over, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today expressed confidence for the future of his country's
aviation industry, saying that "the hard times for Russian
aviation are over," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin spoke at the opening ceremony of the 3rd International
Airspace Show in Zhukovsky, an aviation city east of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
He said he was satisfied with what he had seen at the show, and
was happy that the industry had retained its best researchers and
workers.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the opening ceremony, Economic Minister Yakov
Urinson, said Russia has been and remains a great airspace power,
noting that its aviation industry is sure to overcome the current
economic difficulties with help from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
Some 328 airspace firms from 24 countries, including Boeing,
took part in the exhibition, which is expected to close Sunday.
The show, which is held regularly, is one of five major
international airspace shows in the world. 
</P>
