<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Airlines Increase Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Air Zimbabwe and Zimbabwe
Express Airlines (ZEX) today announced a 30 percent fare increase
on all domestic routes starting from September 1.
</P>
<P>
The two airlines which have been in competition for the past
two years said in a joint statement that the increases were
necessitated by rising operating costs.
</P>
<P>
Spokesmen David Mwenga of Air Zimbabwe and Peter Mukuna of ZEX
said one contributory factor was the rising jet fuel price which
went up twice since last year.
</P>
<P>
"Landing and navigation fees have also gone up. Zimbabwean
aviation authorities recently introduced navigation fees and the
range of our domestic operations is fairly wide," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesmen said there had been increases in salaries, crew
expenses and catering costs.
</P>
<P>
ZEX, a private airline set up two years ago, was the first
indigenous venture to compete with the national airline, Air
Zimbabwe, which is soon to be privatized.
</P>
<P>
A third airline, Expedition Airlines, started operating in
July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
