<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia To Support Fiji Return To Commonwealth: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer announced today in Fiji that Australia supports
the country's bid to rejoin the Commonwealth and said the
embarrassing leak of a secret Australian report would not harm the
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Downer arrived in the Fiji capital city of Suva today for two
days of meetings with the Fiji government, attempting to improve
their relationship following a recent secret paper scandal.
</P>
<P>
Some copies of secret Australian briefing papers, which
described Fiji Foreign Minister Berenado Vunibobo as disappointing
and temperamentally volatile, was left unattended outside a
meeting of South Pacific Forum Economic Ministers in July in
Australia. The papers were obtained by a Reuter correspondent and
published soon after.
</P>
<P>
Fiji had planned to lodge a formal complaint over the report,
which also criticized other Pacific island nations' ministers for
being drunk and corrupt, but today the mood was conciliatory.
</P>
<P>
Fiji Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka offered strong support for
Australian Prime Minister John Howard, saying he thought of him
like an older brother, and asked Downer to leave Fiji with
positive views of the region.
</P>
<P>
"We are not in a canoe that we can go away in this part of the
world," Rabuka was quoted today by the Australian Associated Press
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are forever tied to the affairs of our neighbors, we will
have to interact with each other," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Also today, in an address to a meeting of the Fiji Australia
Business Council, Downer said two way trade between the two
countries rose by 27 percent since 1995, to nearly 590 million
U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also opened today in Suva a three-day
meeting of leading Australian diplomats in the South Pacific
countries.
</P>
<P>
"I have reiterated the continuing importance Australia attaches
to long term constructive bilateral relations with the Pacific
island countries," the foreign minister said in a statement on the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Australia will continue to support Pacific island governments
in their development of improved economic and resource management
policies, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Australia's development assistance to the region in 1997/1998
(the fiscal year starting on July 1, 1997), has been maintained at
previous levels (92 million U.S. dollars) despite budget cuts in
other areas.
</P>
<P>
Fiji was possessed by Britain on October 10, 1874, and remained
a British colony until it gained independence on October 10, 1970,
as a state within the Commonwealth. Fiji's strongman Rabuka
declared Fiji a republic on October 1, 1987. At a meeting in
Canada that year, the Commonwealth Heads of Government formally
declared that Fiji's membership of Commonwealth had lapsed.
</P>
</TEXT>
