<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Government Forces Take Ranariddh's Last </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian government forces
claimed today they had captured the town of O'Smach, the last
major stronghold held by loyalists of Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
But the prince and his followers denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff of the Cambodian Royal Army Ke Kimyan
said in Phnom Penh that the town fell to government forces at
about 1:00 p.m. (0600 GMT) today.
</P>
<P>
Casualties of both sides were still unknown, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Ranariddh's military commander and former
Deputy Commander of the Royal Army Nheuk Bun Chhay fled to
Thailand long ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Ranariddh argued in Bangkok, the capital of Thailand,
that the town was still in his hands.
</P>
<P>
O'Smach, a town near the Thai border, was the last major
stronghold held by troops loyal to Prince Ranariddh, who had been
ousted from office by Second Prime Minister Hun Sen in the July 6
bloody fighting.
</P>
<P>
Since then, part of the prince's supporters began fighting the
government troops, but were pushed back from the capital to the
Thai border.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen ordered government forces to seize O'Smach by August
15. But the uphill town and the land mine-filled jungle around it
made the task extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, more than 20,000 Cambodians, mainly women and
children, fled the town into Thailand to escape the heavy fighting.
</P>
<P>
Thai authorities said on Monday that they opened gates at a
checkpoint on the border and allowed the refugees to enter.
</P>
</TEXT>
