<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Consumer Price Index Unchanged in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers saw an annual
price increase of 1.8 percent for the goods and services included
in the Consumer Price Index (CPI) basket in July, Statistics
Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
The annual consumer price rise was identical to the increase
noted in June, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, transportation charges have risen
considerably, with significant price increases noted for auto
insurance, air travel and new car purchases.
</P>
<P>
Prices for food, utilities, education, alcohol, tobacco, rental
accommodation and clothing also saw some increases.
</P>
<P>
In the same time, "lower mortgage interest charges continued to
benefit consumers," the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Other items that cost less than last July included: computers,
audio and video equipment, household appliances, furniture and
tools.
</P>
<P>
Lower prices for new cars, gasoline, clothing, footwear and
beer were offset by higher prices for air travel, traveler
accommodation and food, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
