<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Lodges Complaint Against Israeli Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has filed a complaint
with the five-nation ceasefire monitoring committee to accuse
Israel of violating the ceasefire understanding and targeting
attack at civilians, the Lebanese Orient Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Monday's bombardment on the southern
Lebanese city of Saida by Israeli troops and its militia ally, the
South Lebanese Army (SLA), in which six people were killed and 45
others wounded.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the radio said Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas
fired at 7:05 am (4:05 GMT) about 30 Katyusha rockets at the
Israeli troops and SLA positions in the north of the buffer zone
in south Lebanon, wounding a woman.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 allegedly to ward off cross-border guerrilla infiltrations
into its northern settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah claimed responsibility for the Katyusha attack
and said in its statement today that this is the response to the
Israeli massacre of civilians.
</P>
<P>
The heavy fighting between Hezbollah guerrillas and Israeli
troops and the SLA took place after the bombing of a car in
southern Lebanon which killed the son and daughter of former SLA
security chief Assad Nasr.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the SLA accused Hezbollah of carrying out the
bombing, and in turn launched a sudden strike upon Saida, which is
outside the "security zone" and hasn't been under attack for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Beirut said that the fighting is most likely to
continue until the delegates of the ceasefire monitoring
committee, comprising of representatives from the US, France,
Syria, Lebanon and Israel, meet to discuss the complaints lodged
by Lebanon and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
