<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Output Increases in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Total crude oil output of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) increased by
some 60,000 barrels per day (bpd) in July, according to a market
survey reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's July output averaged 26.44 million bpd, compared with
26.38 million bpd a month ago, the Middle East Economic
Survey (MEES) showed.
</P>
<P>
The oil output in July was about 1.4 million bpd above OPEC's
self-imposed production ceiling of 25.033 million bpd, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Lower production in Nigeria, mainly as a result of temporary
problems in its production and export system, was counterbalanced
by increased output in Venezuela, Kuwait, Iran and Saudi Arabia,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that a substantial increment is expected
to be added to OPEC output this month following the restart of
Iraqi exports last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
