<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Evidence of Corrupt Acts Inside EU: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- European Commission's (EC)
deputy spokesman Vale de Almeida said today that the EC has found
no evidence of flawed or corrupt actions occurring within its
security bureau.
</P>
<P>
De Almeida made the remark at a press briefing following
allegations by the local Flemish newspaper Morgen (The Morning
Post) on Monday that irregularities, if not corrupt acts, were
spotted from the European Commission's security bureau, where an
official has been removed from the commission's staff car section.
</P>
<P>
De Almeida said the commission, the executive body of the
15-nation European Union, is taking the allegations seriously.
</P>
<P>
The commission is making inquiries to establish that there is
nothing more than the reported irregularities that occurred during
earlier transactions between the security bureau and the security
contractor, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told the press that a certain amount of money was
refunded to the commission in early 1993 after a miscalculation,
which he described as a technical irregularity, was found in a
transaction between the security bureau and the contractor.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman declined to disclose how much money was involved.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on an allegation that 18 people were on
the permanent payroll of the security contractor, who could
reportedly be using the money overpaid by the commission, the
spokesman said that investigations so far have not found any
unjustified payments.
</P>
<P>
When asked why they were not renewing the contract with the
same contractor when the current contract expires at the end of
this year, the spokesman explained that commission security
affairs are now open for tender with new contracts expected to be
signed in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The security contractor of the commission has been providing
routine and special security measures on occasions like the visits
by United States President Bill Clinton and Palestine leader
Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
