<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministry Launches Campaign Against Tooth Decay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China's Health Ministry will
start a campaign against tooth decay on September 20, which is
National Tooth Day, in 11 provinces and autonomous regions which
the Red Army crossed during the Long March (1934-1935).
</P>
<P>
The activity, known as "The New Long March for the Prevention
and Control of Tooth Decay," will be carried out in more than 40
counties in Fujian, Guangdong, Hunan, Jiangxi, Guizhou, Yunnan,
Sichuan, Gansu, Shaanxi provinces and Ningxia Hui and Guangxi
Zhuang autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the year-long activity, which is jointly-organized
by the Health Ministry and the national Committee for Oral Health
(NCOH), is to improve oral hygiene in China's rural areas, said
Yin Dakui, vice-minister of health.
</P>
<P>
The major tasks of the activity include establishing
anti-tooth-decay networks in the local medical organizations,
spreading information about oral hygiene among the local people
and providing dental equipment and oral health care products to
these areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The NCOH will provide hygiene materials and handbooks to poor
areas and send experts there to give instruction.
</P>
<P>
"The activity will promote the development of the national oral
health care, and will take us one step closer to the goal of basic
oral hygiene for all by the year 2000," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
