<HEADLINE> EU Mourns Civilian Deaths in Lebanon, Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union today
mourned for 10 civilians who were killed during bombings in
Lebanon and Israel, a press release here said.
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry spokesman from Luxembourg, which is serving
the six-month rotating presidency of the 15-nation union, appealed
to both sides to respect the ceasefire agreement reached in April
1996, which called for an end to attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire ended 17 days of fighting between the Lebanese
and Israelis in that region.
</P>
<P>
"The bombardment against Saida and Jezzine in Lebanon and
against Kyriat Schmonah in Israel on Monday resulted in 10 deaths
and dozens of injured among the civilian population," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The attack was the bloodiest against Lebanese civilians in more
than a year. Artillery shells were reportedly fired by pro-Israel
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
The shells were fired from Jezzine, an enclave that lies north
of the security zone that the Israeli army and its Lebanese allies
occupy in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The attacks were launched in retaliation for a roadside bombing
that killed three Lebanese civilians also on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the last nine days no less than 25 people, more than half of
them civilians, were killed in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
