<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Student Killed in Clash With Security Men in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- One student died in a
shoot-out between security forces and a group of protesting
students at the campus of a nursing school in the capital
Freetown here Monday, the State Radio said Today.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out started when seven students of the nursing
school opened fire on members of a passing security patrol, who
returned fire, the radio quoted Captain Abubakarr Kamara, the
officer in charge of the Western Area Security Patrol (WASP) in
the Department of Defense, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Two university students and a local fisherman were arrested in
different parts of the city for carrying firearms and other
offensive weapons, Kamara said.
</P>
<P>
The radio said a total of 35 people have been detained at the
maximum security prison in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, students of the Njala University College in the
south of Sierra Leone said today they did not support Monday's
failed demonstration called by the National Union of Sierra Leone
Students (NUSS).
</P>
<P>
President of the college's student union Yosuf Bah told Xinhua
in an interview, "my colleagues could be cautious in resisting
the military."
</P>
<P>
"It can cost us our lives as I don't believe that students
should take to the streets to demonstrate their protest against a
well-armed military regime," Bah warned.
</P>
<P>
"Our interest is to go back to college as soon as possible as
we already missed our final year examinations on June 11," Bah
added.
</P>
<P>
The NUSS called a democracy march to urge the military regime
of Major Johnny Paul Koroma to hand over power back to the
civilian government it ousted on May 25.
</P>
<P>
The military junta had banned the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the military regime has appealed to
the Guinean government to reopen the Sierra Leone embassy in
Conakry, one day after it was closed following unauthorized
demonstrations by pro-democracy Sierra Leone refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement broadcast over State Radio, the
regime said it "frowns on the behaviors of these Sierra Leoneans
who have taken undue advantage of the hospitality of the friendly
people of Guinea." 
</P>
</TEXT>
