<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading Banker Lauds Financial Sector Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China's financial sector has
experienced steady and sound development since the 14th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China in 1992 and the central
bank will remain committed to a moderately tight monetary policy
for a period of time, according to a senior banking official.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, the
central bank, said in an interview with Xinhua that the steady and
healthy development of China's financial sector is reflected in
several aspects.
</P>
<P>
First of all, the financial macro-control capability has
markedly strengthened, Dai said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the implementation of the moderately tight monetary
policy and the use of a basket of financial tools to regulate the
money supply, the annual growth rate of the supply of broad money,
known as M2, which is the combination of cash in circulation plus
all types of deposits, dropped from 34.4 percent in 1994 to 25.2
percent last year. This year the rate is expected to be less than
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that, over the past five years, the framework of a
financial legal system has basically taken shape, which has in
turn effectively helped improve financial supervision.
</P>
<P>
The financial legal system consists of the Law on the People's
Bank of China, which is considered the centerpiece, and the
Commercial Bank Law, the Insurance Law and the Bill Law. It also
includes some more-detailed rules and regulations such as the
Provisional Rules on the Management of Bank Credits, the
Provisions on the Management of Financial Institutions, the
General Rules on Loans, the Provisional Rules on the Management of
Sponsoring Banks, and the Provincial Rules on the Management of
Credit Card Business.
</P>
<P>
The enactment and implementation of the laws and rules have
provided a guarantee for the divided operation and management of
business in banking, securities, insurance and trust, and thereby
helped improve the financial order, Dai said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading Banker Lauds Financial Sector Development (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the years the central bank has considered curbing
inflation as its prime task, adhered to a moderately tight
monetary policy and properly conducted financial macro-control,
thereby allowing the monetary policy to play a due role in the
country's overall macro-control effort, Dai said.
</P>
<P>
The financial situation so far this year has been stable and
healthy, as reflected by a reasonable growth of the money supply
and an increase of lending that has basically met the requirements
of economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that right now and in the next period of time the
central bank will continue to follow the moderately tight monetary
policy and, at the same time, make appropriate fine-tunings of
macro control and improve the quality of financial services in
order to facilitate the sustained, rapid and healthy development
of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The state banks must strictly control their loan portfolio and
effectively improve cash management, Dai pointed out.
</P>
<P>
While focusing support on state-owned enterprises, the state
banks should also reasonably satisfy the requirements for credits
of enterprises with different types of ownership, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dai added that while concentrating its support on some large
and medium-sized enterprises, the state banks should also, in line
with industrial policies, support the development of competitive
small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The state banks should also support inter-enterprise
cooperation, help to nurture industrial conglomerates, and
facilitate strategic restructuring of enterprises in different
economic zones, the governor urged.
</P>
<P>
Provisions for bad loans in the state banks should be well
managed in accordance with relevant rules and regulations in order
to support enterprises' merger, bankruptcy and re-employment of
the laid-offs, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading Banker Lauds Financial Sector Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central bank governor listed the increasingly deepening of
financial reforms as another major achievement in the financial
sector in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Reform in the state-owned commercial banks has accelerated over
the years. At the same time, three policy-oriented banks -- the
State Development Bank, the Export and Import Bank of China, and
the Agricultural Development Bank of China -- have been founded to
take over the policy-directed business from the state banks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, urban cooperative banks are being set up in 100
selected cities whereas rural credit cooperatives are being
reformed, Dai said.
</P>
<P>
The measures already taken have combined to contribute to the
formation and perfection of a setup of financial organizations led
by the People's Bank of China, with the state-owned commercial
banks as the major players.
</P>
<P>
Over the recent years China has also established a foreign
exchange market and an interbank money market, started the open
market operation on a trial basis, and made the yuan, the national
currency, convertible for current-account transactions.
</P>
<P>
The recent years have also withnessed a successful and
continuous opening of the financial sector to the rest of the
world, Dai said.
</P>
<P>
To date 23 cities and the island province of Hainan, which is
also a special economic zone, have been approved as pioneer places
where overseas financial institutions are allowed to set up
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, overseas financial institutions had opened
a total of 540 representative offices and 161 operational agencies
in China, with their total assets reaching 33 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has allowed a number of overseas financial
institutions in Shanghai to deal with yuan-based business on a
limited basis in the city's Pudong New Area, a burgeoning
financial and trade district separated from downtown Shanghai by
the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
The governor also noted that the asset value of the financial
sector has grown rapidly over the recent years. Statistics
indicate that the total assets of all Chinese financial
institutions were valued at 13.28 trillion yuan (about 1.6
trillion US dollars), nearly ten trillion yuan more than in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
