<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Shuttle Discovery Returns to Earth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle Discovery
with six astronauts returned to Earth today after one day delay
with a satellite containing valuable information about the Earth's
ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
The space plane glided through a pale, mostly clear sky and
landed at Kennedy Space Center just after sunrise, ending a
12-day, 7.5 million kilometer journey for science.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the morning, flight controllers had kept close watch
on the hazy sky over Kennedy, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, NASA decided to delay the landing because of fears
that pre-dawn haze might turn into fog though no actual fog
developed later.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from NASA said that the crew achieved all its
objectives despite problems with some of the 24 payloads aboard
the spaceship.
</P>
<P>
The astronauts spent their last full day in orbit swinging
around the ozone-monitoring satellite that they retrieved on
Saturday. The satellite has been set free from the spaceship for
nine days.
</P>
<P>
The Germany-made satellite contains nine days' worth of
atmospheric data, enough to fill about 500 kilograms of computer
disks.
</P>
<P>
The astronauts also successfully raised with a Japan-made robot
arm the 3500 kilogram satellite high above the open cargo bay to
see what it would be like to move parts of the future
international space stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
