<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Battles Strong Typhoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Local people in east China's
Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces and Shanghai Municipality are
recovering from a powerful typhoon which swept through the areas
last night.
</P>
<P>
Known as "Number 11," or "Typhoon Winnie," the typhoon first
struck the coastal city of Wenling in Zhejiang Province. The
province's coastal belts, in particular, suffered the most damage.
</P>
<P>
In Wenling, strong tidal waves damaged 26 sections of 13
coastal dikes and flooded 34 towns and townships. Some 30,000
local residents were temporarily trapped in their homes due to the
water gushing from the broken dikes and eventually moved out of
the dangerous areas before the typhoon hit.
</P>
<P>
High winds, tidal waves and thunderstorms affected 32 coastal
dikes and a dozen harbors in Zhoushan, a city of archipelagos in
Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
Airports in Ningbo, Wenzhou, Zhoushan and Hangzhou have been
closed. Some sections of road were washed away and telecom routes
cut down in the thunderstorm. One ship in Sanmen County sank.
</P>
<P>
The Qiantang Dyke, critical for the protection of Hangzhou, the
provincial capital, today remained under the constant supervision
of local people and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the foresight of the local governments, some one
million residents in the coastal region were moved to safer places
before the typhoon, keeping the damage and injuries to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's key economic center, was also affected by the
typhoon and accompanying storms and tidal waves.
</P>
<P>
The Hongqiao International Airport was closed at 7 p.m. last
night. Some 95 flights were cancelled and more than 100
delayed. Latest reports said that the airport resumed operation
early this morning.
</P>
<P>
River and rail transport in the city were also seriously
influenced by the bad weather.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, neighboring Zhejiang, also reported big storms and
tidal waves. The provincial and local governments have led
residents in the work of draining waterlogged areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
