<HEADLINE> Senior Diplomat for Sino-Japanese Non-Governmental Friendship Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Sun Pinghua, president of the
China-Japan Friendship Association and a famed Chinese expert on
Japan who witnessed the development of Sino-Japanese relations
after World War II, died of illness here on August 15. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
When Sun was ill and at the time of his death, Chinese leaders
Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Li Ruihuan, Zhu Rongji, Hu Jintao,
and Rong Yiren, expressed their sympathy.
</P>
<P>
Among those who paid last respects to Sun here this morning
were Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing; vice-chairmen of the
Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress Wang
Guangying and Buhe; vice-chairmen of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference Wu Xueqian and
Zhao Puchu; officials from the Chinese government, Beijing
Municipal government and non-governmental friendship bodies,
veterans dealing with China-Japan affairs, and Sun's friends.
</P>
<P>
Sun was cremated here today.
</P>
<P>
After Sun's death, the Japanese government, Japan-China
friendship offices, and Japanese personages from various circles
sent messages of condolence and wreaths, and praised Sun for his
contribution to the development of Sino-Japanese friendship.
</P>
<P>
Sun, formerly named Qi Shoufu, was born in 1917 in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, and went to Japan to study in 1939.
</P>
<P>
Sun started to deal with Japanese issues in 1952, thus becoming
a pioneer of Sino-Japanese non-governmental diplomacy. He also did
a lot of work for the realization of the normalization of
Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
