<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Immigrants to Israel Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A total of 33,000 immigrants
arrived in Israel so far this year, representing a 16 percent drop
over the number in the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A report of Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics released today
shows shows that during the January-July period 26,900 immigrants
arrived from the former Soviet Union, 17 percent less than that of
last year. In 1996, immigrants to Israel totaled 70,600, of whom
58,900 were from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the figures show a 6 percent decrease over the number
of the same period in 1996 in immigration from the American
countries, which stood at 2,500 people. About 1,000 came from the
United States, or a 9 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Among the immigrants arriving this year, 30 percent are below
the age of 19, and 44 percent between ages of 20 and 49.
</P>
<P>
Anomie Blumenthal, chairwoman of the Knesset (parliament)
Immigration Committee, said the statistics indicated that Israel
wasn't doing enough to absorb immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"The wave of (terrorist) attacks and the negative image...has
not encouraged immigration," she said.
</P>
<P>
But other officials blamed the decline in the number of
newcomers on a drying reservoir of potential immigrants,
particularly in the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Immigration and absorption ministry spokesman Arik Hellman
attributed the decline in the number of immigrants to Israel to
the improving of conditions of Jews abroad, especially in Russia,
where many Jews can find jobs. Meanwhile, unemployment rate in
Israel has been rising. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
