<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Sidelined By Stock Market Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
weaker today following a fall in the price of gold overnight and
news that the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) retained a very
optimistic outlook on inflation for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
Overnight in the United States, the gold price fell 4.6 U.S.
dollars to 321.1 an ounce and was at 321.5 late local today.
</P>
<P>
The RBA's August bulletin containing its quarterly update on
financial markets and the economy said monetary policy was
providing some expansionary inputs to the economy.
</P>
<P>
The currency finished at 73.74 U.S. cents down from 74.26
previously, and it had traded as low as 73.65 U.S. cents during
the afternoon session.
</P>
<P>
"After the bulletin, it reacted to headlines about inflation
and expectations built quickly in dealers minds about a future
rate cut," said NAB foreign exchange manager Derek Price.
</P>
<P>
And while economists said, the RBA's quarterly report does not
ruled out the prospect of another rate cut, monetary policy was
likely to remain on hold for now.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended at 87.12 from
87.00 against yen and at 1.3539 from 1.3458 against mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
