<HEADLINE> Liaoning to Become China's Leading Flower Production Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
province has now become the country's largest bulb-root flower
planting and cut flower producer.
</P>
<P>
Situate in temperate zone with favorable light, humid and
temperature for flower growing, Liaoning is abundant in flower
resources like azalea, Chinese rose, and other 150 kinds of wild
flowers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that by the end of 1996, flower planting
acreage reached 2,410 hectares, a 100-fo1d increase over that of
five years ago. Cut flower and potted flower production bases of
Liaoning were set up in the cities of Shenyang and Anshan.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning now has more than 170 enterprises engaged in flower
business, with over 500 flower strains. Flower products began to
enter markets in Japan and the Republic of Korea, with the annual
output value of nearly one billion yuan (120 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
To accelerate flower industry, Liaoning introduced quintessence
flowers like lily and tulip. It invested 30 million yuan (3.6
million US dollars) in setting up flower demonstration farms or
flower centers, with the first completed in July.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is setting up flower trading center in Shenyang,
flower wholesale market in Dalian, and three other flower markets
in its western and northern parts. It is estimated that by the
year 2000 the flower planting acreage will reach 3,300 hectares,
with the output value of 1.5 billion yuan (181 million US
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
