<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Defeats Currency Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) chief executive Joseph Yam said that speculation against
the Hong Kong dollar last Thursday and Friday had been defeated,
local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The speculative activities were all small deals between 20
million and 30 million U.S. dollars, today's Hong Kong Standard
quoted Yam as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that none of the bigger hedge funds was operating
against the local currency Friday, according to another English
newspaper South China Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
"Some people who sold the Hong Kong dollar on Friday have
bought back on Monday in the London trades," Yam said. "We have
won the game so far with the help of the banks which pushed the
interest rates up."
</P>
<P>
The monetary official said he felt comfortable with the
exchange rates at 7.74 to 7.75 HK dollars to the U.S. dollar since
the official peg between the two currencies is at about 7.80 HK
dollars to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed his confidence in the fundamental strength of the
local economy, saying that Hong Kong, which comes to be a
service-oriented economy, would not lose its competitive edge even
if other Asian currencies were depreciated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Most Crowded Nation in South Asia: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Minister for
Population Welfare Abida Hussain said today the country is the
most crowded one in the region in terms of population intensity.
</P>
<P>
A country-wide survey has revealed that six persons live in a
house whereas the desired family size was four per house, Abida
said when addressing an international conference held in Karachi,
Pakistan's largest city, according to a report by Associated Press
of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make a choice between the 'sustainable' or 'non-
sustainable' development process and decide which side we wanted
to go in next 15 years," Abida was quoted as saying at the
conference named "South Asia '97 - Toward a Progressive Economic
Union".
</P>
<P>
Abida said Pakistan's present population is 132 million and
environment does not allow the country to exceed beyond 200
million people.
</P>
<P>
For a sustainable development, the family size has to be
reduced from the present four to two children in next five years
to contain population growth, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
