<HEADLINE> Chief Executive Optimistic About HK Sharemarket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), Tung Chee Hwa, said
today that he is optimistic about the future of the Hong Kong
sharemarket, though the Hang Seng Index finished the day with a
loss of 619 points.
</P>
<P>
The fall from the previous close of 16,096 set last Friday,
partly due to the influence from Wall Street's slide in currency
trading, will soon be curbed, experts here believed.
</P>
<P>
Stock markets were lower around the world Monday, following
Friday's steep 247-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrial
average on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, stock markets in Japan, the
Philippines, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, Indonesia, Australia
and New Zealand have also been slumping.
</P>
<P>
"People are still uncertain about how long speculation on the
local currency is going to drag on," the experts said, adding that
the Hang Seng Index was still at a very high level and predicting
the 33-member blue-chip index would plunge by about 800 to 1,000
points in the near future.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters here earlier today, SAR Chief
Executive Tung stressed that he has strong confidence in the
fundamental strength of Hong Kong's economy, noting that any
attempts to hit the Hong Kong dollar would be defeated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
