<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torrential Rains Kill one in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A 30-year-old man drowned during
torrential rains in the Philippine capital of Manila after he fell
into a creek on his way home, the Philippine News Agency said
today.
</P>
<P>
The victim, Joey de la Cruz, drowned at the Lilac Creek in
Masinag, Antopolo, in Manila, while going home during heavy rains
last night, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers are still searching for his body, it said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first casualty of the torrential rains which
started in the northern Philippines on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The torrential rains intensified by typhoon have caused massive
flooding in the northern Philippines, affecting business
operations and normal lives of people in Manila and the rest of
Luzon.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports by the official Disaster Coordination Council
said that two to three feet thick of mud water rampaged through
Pasig-Potrero river in Pamanga and two feet thick mud water at
Sacobia river in Bamban, in Central Luzon.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that some 10,000 families living in high-risk
areas near the river have been alerted to take precautionary
measures in case of continuous heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of Manila, thousands of families were evacuated
to schools, chapels and village halls, the Department of Social
Welfare and Development said.
</P>
<P>
The torrential rains forced some government offices, shops and
schools to close as the flooding prevented people from going to
work.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philippine Airlines canceled 13 more domestic and
three more international flights scheduled for today because of
the monsoon rains.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
