<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Work Suspended in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Work in the Philippines'
government agencies and state-run corporations were suspended
today due to heavy flooding caused by torrential monsoon rains in
the northern and central Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ruben Torres ordered in an announcement the
suspension of services in all government agencies and firms,
except some vital ones.
</P>
<P>
Transactions were also canceled on the Philippine Stock
Exchange and the country's currency market due to the flooding
which interrupted transportation in most parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Many low-lying parts of the streets in the capital city were
flooded by waist-deep or knee-deep water due to continuing monsoon
rains. Many commuters and cars were seen stranded along the
flooded streets.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 families have been evacuated to higher and
safer ground in Metro Manila due to flash floods menacing their
houses in low-lying areas.
</P>
<P>
In central Luzon, heavy rains loosened tons of volcanic ash on
Mount Pinatub and turned it into mud flows, posing threat to
several villages at the foot of the volcanic mountain.
</P>
<P>
Massive monsoon rains, intensified by typhoon Winnie, began to
batter Luzon Island and Visayas since Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
