<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Enterprises Change Operation Mechanism (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Huge profit has been generated
for enterprises in east China's coastal areas which have changed
their operations systems in response to market demand, People's
Daily, the leading newspaper in China, reported today.
</P>
<P>
The front page article pointed out that the key to a successful
enterprise lies in the constant innovation of its products. It
cited the Ziguang Machinery Corporation Ltd. in Shanghai, China's
largest industrial city, as an example.
</P>
<P>
This enterprise, the largest of its kind in Shanghai, once was
on the verge of bankruptcy. In early 1995, it still suffered
losses of over 11 million yuan (about 1.3 million US dollars), and
had to lay off 30 percent of its employees.
</P>
<P>
After careful market analysis, it presented in 1995 three new
products, which were all in urgent market demand. Sales of these
goods accounted for 30 percent of the company's overall business
volume of that year.
</P>
<P>
In the following year, the company developed four other new
products, which brought in some 80 percent of its total profit.
And the eight new products the company took out this year are
expected to contribute some 90 percent of the annual profit.
</P>
<P>
Within only two years, the products of Ziguang have gained high
popularity across the country and also in the global market, with
the company's per capita sales volume four times as much as the
average index in China's machine-building industry.
</P>
<P>
"The most important reason for Ziguang's success is that it has
found a channel to link its own products with the market," the
article said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
