<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Oil Group Confirms Discovery of Offshore Oil in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The French oil group Elf-Aquitaine
today confirmed that it has discovered a big offshore oilfield
1,360 meters underwater off Angola, which appears to be the
biggest oilfield ever discovered in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The new oilfield, baptized Dalia, is the second oilfield
discovered off Angola by Elf-Aquitaine, which discovered the
Girassol oilfield in the same area deemed to have the same oil
potential as the Brazilian Campos basin.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary tests, Dalia has between three and 3.5
billion barrels of oil reserve, compared with between 900 million
and 1.4 billion barrels in Dirassol, Agence France-Presse quoted
Elf officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Both Dalia and Dirassol are located about 200 kilometers
northwest of Luanda, the capital of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Elf said that the commercial potential of Dalia is yet to be
evaluated by experts, but its discovery confirmed the huge oil
reserve in the offshore area of Angola, where experts think exist
three to five big oilfields.
</P>
<P>
The Elf Exploration Angola, an affiliate of Elf-Aquitaine, is
operating 35 percent of the oil production in Angola, in
collaboration with several other Western oil groups including Esso
Exploration Angola, British Petroleum Exploration Angola, Statoil,
Norsk Hydro, and Fina Exploration.
</P>
<P>
Girassol will begin producing oil by 2000, with a primary
production capacity of 100,000 barrels per day, and a potential of
200,000 barrels per day, said Elf officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
