<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Start Reforms Dialogue Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The constitutional reform talks
between the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) and the
Opposition are scheduled to commence on August 20, according to a
"Kenya Times" report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted Secretary of the nine-man
Religious Mediating Team Rev. Mulava Musyimi as saying
that the Muslim community's two representatives were back to the
Religious Community Mediation Committee.
</P>
<P>
Muslim members of the committee last Friday pulled out of the
dialogue, charging that the chairman of the dialogue committee was
not impartial.
</P>
<P>
Musyimi noted that the post of the committee set up last
Wednesday had been abolished to be replaced by rotating
chairpersons.
</P>
<P>
The National Convention Executive Council (NCEC), an umbrella
body of opposition parties, announced last Thursday the formation
of a 50-member team to hold dialogue with the ruling KANU.
</P>
<P>
The KANU Parliament Group is scheduled to have a meeting this
morning to do preparations for the coming dialogue with the
Opposition tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The KANU National Executive Council last month decided to
effect constitutional, legal and administrative changes before
the forthcoming General Elections to be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Attorney General Amos Wako has since published two
bills, seeking to repeal or amend some of contentious laws, and
to empower President Daniel arap Moi to appoint a commission to
review constitutional changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
