<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Community Clash up to 50 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Continued clashes between two
communities in southwest Nigeria's Osun State have left 50 people
dead, 160 others hospitalized and at least 70 houses burnt,
despite a dusk-to-dawn curfew.
</P>
<P>
about 45 of those receiving treatment at hospitals are
reported on the danger list, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The situtaion with the presence of hundreds of armed anit-riot
policemen could not be said to have improved as the atmosphere in
the two communities are still charged and tension soaked.
</P>
<P>
The event began with a peaceful demonstration last Friday by
about 5,000 Modakeke youths, in protest of relocating the
Ife-East local government headquarters from Modakeke to Oke-Ogbo
in Ile-Ife.
</P>
<P>
The denouncement of the Ife leader by Modakeke youths
reportedly raised anger of the Ife people. When more students
joined both sides on Saturday, fighting escalated from throwing
stones to each other to exchange of gunfire and burn of houses.
</P>
<P>
The clashes, which calmed down about mid-Sunday after the
arrival of anti-riot policemen, resumed hours later and lasted
till the next day. Dane guns, matchets, axes and broken bottles
were used by both sides.
</P>
<P>
Local government and traditional rulers have urged the warring
communities to embrace dialogue to avoid further bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time fighting broke out between the two
communities. One politician from Modakeke was killed in 1983 in
an attack launched by thugs hired by the rival party.
</P>
<P>
The ugly incident, before which the peoples of Ile-Ife and
Modakeke area were living together in peace, sowed the seed of
discard between them.
</P>
<P>
The Ife-Modakeke clash is the second of similar nature in the
country this year.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, bloodshed caused by the move of a local
government site from the Ijaw community to where the Itsekiri
people live claimed the lives of tens of people in the oil
producing city of Warri in southern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The communal crisis led to huge losses to oil production with
a big number of properties damaged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
