<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian State-owned Commercial Bank to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's state-owned
National Bank of Commerce (NBC) is expected to be dissolved on
September 30 to give way to two new banks which become
operational the following day.
</P>
<P>
This proposal is to be deliberated in the National Assembly
and waiting for endorsement next week, according to local press
reports today.
</P>
<P>
Government bills moved in the National Assembly say that the
two new banks -- the National Bank of Commerce (NBC) Ltd. and the
National Microfinance Bank (NMB) Ltd. are to start operations on
October 1.
</P>
<P>
The move will legally initiate the restructuring of NBC and
pave way for its privatization.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa told some members of parliament from
the ruling party earlier that NBC is a big burden to the
country's economy as it has been suffering huge losses, forcing
the government to pump in tax-payers' money in billions of
shillings (one US dollar equals 600 shillings) for its survival.
</P>
<P>
However, several politicians and pressure groups have fears
that privatization of NBC will deprive the people in the rural
areas, particularly small holders such as farmers and business
operators access to credit.
</P>
<P>
The bills say that unlike the present bank which was
established by a statute in 1967 and given monopoly in the
country's commercial banking, the new banks will be incorporated
as companies by September 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
