<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Praises Teamsters Union, UPS Reach Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has praised the agreement reached by the Teamsters union and
United Parcel Service (UPS) Late Monday night to end a 15-day
strike that crippled package deliveries nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, following 80 hours of talks over five days, was
announced by Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, who was joined at an
early morning news conference by Teamsters President Ron Carey and
the company's chief negotiator, David Murray.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, whose administration had resisted calls form business
groups to intervene and end the strike, praised both sides, saying
that "the issues that were at the heart of their negotiations are
important to our nation's economic strength and to all Americans."
</P>
<P>
Murray said that both sides compromised to reach the deal. "To
our employees: we hope to welcome you back very soon," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Murray and Carey declined to provide details of the
agreement, but a source familiar with the deal said it was for a
five-year contract that increased the base wage for part-time
workers and did not include a contentious pension proposal made by
the company.
</P>
<P>
It also would convert thousands of part-time jobs into
full-time positions.
</P>
<P>
The union's national bargaining committee and local union
leaders who represent UPS workers were told to fly to Washington
on Tuesday to receive the package for approval -- the final steps
before a rank-and-file vote.
</P>
<P>
The Teamsters, representing nearly two-thirds of the UPS' 302,000
U.S. employees, went on strike August 4.
</P>
<P>
During the strike, the Teamster Union insisted that the company
add more full-time positions. It also opposed the UPS' plan to
withdraw from the Teamsters' multi-employer pension and health
funds and establish a separate benefit fund for UPS workers.
</P>
<P>
Carey had insisted that the union would not agree to any offer
unless it included more full-time jobs and limits on
subcontracting.
</P>
<P>
About 58 percent of UPS jobs are filled by part-time workers,
and their eight-dollars-an-hour base salary has not increased
since 1982. The company created 46,000 jobs last year, 38,000 of
them being part-time.
</P>
<P>
In addition to an annual 1.5 percent wage increase for
full-time workers, the company's original offer included a 3,060
dollars bonus for full-time employees. Full-time UPS drivers earn
19.95 dollar an hour on average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
