<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Peso Depreciates Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine currency of peso
has dropped to another record low of 30.07 peso against the U.S.
dollar after a six-day straight plunge which culminated on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since Southeast Asian currencies were attacked by speculators
in July, the peso has fallen by 14 percent to the present level
from a fixed rate of 26.4 peso to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the new round of depreciation was attributed to
the pressure exerted by other declining Southeast Asian currencies
and the Philippine Central Bank's decision to cut key interest
rates and stay away from the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
After the International Monetary Fund provided a bail-out
package to shore up the Thai currency, the baht is stabilizing.
However, other Asian currencies soon succumbed to new speculative
attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian ringgit plunged by 3.5 percent to a 41-month low
of 2.7430 ringgit against the dollar on August 12. Two days later,
the Indonesian rupiah plummeted to 2,762 rupiah to one dollar, a
record low since 1973, forcing the country to float it freely.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore dollar, the safe heaven currency of Asia, also
fell victim to the current currency turmoil sweeping the region,
tumbling to a three-year record low of 1.514 per U.S. dollar last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson said the baht
has so far dipped 23.2 percent, the rupiah 17.1 percent, the
ringgit 9.5 percent and the Singapore dollar 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The whole region is experiencing the same pressure and the
fall of the peso was not due to a weak domestic economy", analysts
said, "The new attacks on the peso could not be remedied
internally, but should be addressed by the region as a whole."
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, added that the peso's situation was
aggravated by the Central Bank's recent move to cut key interest
rates and the adoption of a hand-off policy at the foreign
exchange market.
</P>
<P>
To preserve the country's economic gains, the bank recently
lowered its overnight borrowing rate from 32 percent to 14 percent
while the lending rate, the term borrowing rate and other key
interest rates are also dropping.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the declining interest rates reduce the incentive
for investors to hold their funds in pesos and make it less costly
to buy up the greenback, allowing some commercial banks to play
around the market.
</P>
<P>
"Although there was a strong demand for dollar from importers,
it is not enough to push the rate to the present level. Banks are
just playing with the market, testing at what level the rate would
settle," analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Following the suit of Malaysia and Indonesia, the Central Bank
also abandoned its futile defense of the peso. From August 11, it
has been absent at the foreign exchange market, neither selling
nor buying U.S. dollars to stabilize the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
When the peso was first attacked in early July, the bank
actively intervened in the local market by selling 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars in less than 10 days and raising the overnight
borrowing rate to a record high of 32 percent. But all the
measures failed to protect the peso.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that it would continue its hand-off policy this
week, determined to let the market decide the rate between the
peso and the dollar even as currency traders expect the peso to
dip further.
</P>
<P>
"The drop of the peso is not over. The rate would went up
further in the next few days considering the continued weakening
of other Asian currencies and if the Central Bank continues
staying away from the market," analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
