<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Trade With China Rises Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral trade and investment
between South Korea and China have marked a drastic rise since the
two countries normalized diplomatic ties in 1992, with an annual
increase rate of 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics by the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy show
that Seoul's two-way trade with Beijing has more than quadrupled
to 19.9 billion U.S. dollars last year from 4.4 billion dollars
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the nation's exports to China rose from 1
billion dollars in 1991 to 11.4 billion dollars last year,
registering an annual increase rate of 62.5 percent, which far led
the 3.3 percent and 5 percent for the United States and Japan in
the same period.
</P>
<P>
Exports to China shared 8.8 percent of its total foreign
shipments last year, compared with 1.4 percent in 1991, pushing up
China as the country's third-largest export destination after the
U.S. and Japan.
</P>
<P>
China is now South Korea's third-largest import source, with
exports to South Korea representing 5.7 percent of the country's
total foreign purchase last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Korean is a leading investor in China, taking
the top spot in the number of cases and the second in investment
amount.
</P>
<P>
The country's direct business investment in China stood at 2.66
billion dollars with 2,876 projects by the end of last year,
accounting for 2 percent of China's total direct foreign
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
