<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Tanzania, Zimbabwe to Implement Commodity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Uganda, Tanzania and Zimbabwe
are to kick off later this year a three-year regional commodity
project to boost the credit worthiness of their exporters,
reported the local newspaper "The Crusader" today.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources here were quoted as saying that under the 9.1
million U.S. Dollar project, collateral warehouse systems will be
established in the economies of the three countries over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the Common Fund for Commodities (CFC)-backed
project is expected to kick off later this year, with the
executing countries contributing some counter-funding, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The fund will offer a grant of slightly over 3.7 million
Dollars, and a loan of 1.74 million dollars is expected from the
Bank of the Preferential Trade Area (PTA).
</P>
<P>
Local banks will provide 787,000 Dollars, the International
Coffee Organisation 15,000 Dollars and the rest will come from
implementing countries.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's contribution towards the project is estimated at
538,503 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The collateral warehouse system is enabling exporters borrow
funds for their operation once their commodities have entered
their warehouses.
</P>
<P>
Some eastern African countries including Zambia and
Mozambique, have reportedly adopted the system.
</P>
<P>
The project, once implemented, will benefit all export
commodities, especially coffee.
</P>
<P>
This would be a big relief to small coffee exporters here in
Uganda who are operating dismally due to the failure to raise
pre-financing funds from Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
