<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Registers Steady Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Continuing steady growth of
China's national economy during July featured a slight dip in
industrial production and investment in fixed assets, a rapid
increase of foreign trade, and a low inflation rate, according to
a monthly economic report released by State Statistical Bureau
(SSB).
</P>
<P>
Industrial enterprises above the county-level generated a July
value-added volume of 162.5 billion yuan, a real term rise of 8.4
percent over the corresponding 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
The July heat wave sparked slower than average growth for the
the industrial sector when compared to the first half of this
year. However, the sales rate for industrial products reached
96.34 percent, the highest level since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report showed that China's industrial sector achieved a
value-added volume of 1.15 trillion yuan for the January-July
period, up 11 percent from the previous year's same period, with
the sales rate rising by 0.7 percentage points to 94.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
Investments in fixed assests during the first seven months of
the year hit 639.2 billion yuan, up 10.5 percent from the previous
year's period and 3.8 percentage points lower than the average for
the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, July retail sales for consumer goods
reached 210.3 billion yuan, a real term year-on-year rise of 12.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Total retail sales for the January-July period jumped 12
percent to 1.5 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The July foreign trade volume of 28.4 billion US dollars
represented an 19.8 percent increase over the 1996 period. Exports
were up 25.7 percent to 15.6 billion dollars, with imports rising
13.4 percent to 12.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The nation's revenues grew by 24.6 percent on annual basis,
with expenditures rising by only 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
SSB statistics show that deposits in China's financial
institutions grew by 68.5 billion yuan, or some 58.1 billion yuan
less than in the corresponding 1996 period. Loans fell by 25.7
billion yuan to 54.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's inflation rate fluctuated slightly in July with retail
prices rising by a mere 0.6 percent and consumer prices edging up
by 2.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
