<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Environmental Monitoring System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China has established a
nationwide environmental monitoring system with more than 4,000
stations staffed by over 70,000 technical personnel.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yangzu, deputy director of the National Environmental
Protection Agency (Nepa), told conferees attending today's opening
of the Fifth National Environmental Monitoring Conference that
ministries and governments in different administrative regions
have engaged in joint efforts to guarantee that the system
operates smoothly.
</P>
<P>
China's Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-1995) featured the
establishment of a "National Environmental Monitoring Network" and
four special transregional networks covering the Yangtze River
Valley, offshore areas and various other environmentally
vulnerable regions.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that urban monitoring stations regularly
monitor more than 80 percent of atmospheric, water and noise
pollution levels, with rural stations providing 56 percent
coverage in their respective areas.
</P>
<P>
A number of stations also monitor soil conditions, wildlife and
various ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
Monitoring centers have enabled local governments and related
departments throughout the nation to reach appropriate decisions
on environmental management.
</P>
<P>
China has also drafted a plan for the development of an even
more extensive environmental monitoring system between 1996-2000,
and a year 2010 blueprint to perfect the system by placing
priority on the expansion of special monitoring networks and urban
centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Job Creation Urged For Uganda's Former WNBF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 former rebels
of the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) are in need of farm tools and
other ways for their lives, "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
John Obala, Council Secretary of Koboko District in northwest
Uganda, told the paper that former rebels are visiting his office
for capital to start their business or help in finding jobs.
</P>
<P>
The WNBF rebels surrendered to the government and were freed
after the collapse of WNBF in mid-March. But hundreds of the
former rebels captured by the government troops are still in
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
But the freed former rebels have found no jobs for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Obala appealed to the government to take steps to get the
former rebels resettled, otherwise, he warned, they could engage
in negative activities and become a threat to local security.
</P>
<P>
An early report said Uganda National Rescue Front Part Two
(UNRF II), a breakaway group from WNBF, have recruited some 1,000
youths in the area for military training in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The authorities concerned have noticed the need of the former
WNBF members, with the Uganda army having conscripted 700 of them.
</P>
<P>
James Kazini, Commander of the fourth division, said the
Uganda army absorbed some 2,000 of them to escort convoys in the
northwest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
