<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Appeals to Parliament to Approve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Iranian new President Mohammad
Khatami, a former liberal-minded cleric, today called on the hard
liner-dominated parliament to approve his cabinet lineup.
</P>
<P>
The parliament began debate on the proposed 22-member cabinet
this morning.
</P>
<P>
In his opening statement to the parliament session, Khatami
defended his choices by assuring the MP's that Iran's Supreme
Leader Ali Khamenei was not opposed to any of his ministers.
</P>
<P>
"I have taken caution that I would not choose anyone whom the
Leadership (Khamenei) would oppose, although the Leadership is
above such mundane opposition," said Khatami, who was sworn in on
August 4 as the fifth president.
</P>
<P>
According to Iran's constitution, every single candidate for
the ministerial post must win the parliament's vote of confidence
before undertaking the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing conservatives headed by Parliament Speaker Ali
Akbar Nateq-Nouri currently form a parliamentary majority
occupying 140 seats of the 270-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
While the liberal camp, which supports the economic policy of
Former President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, take up about 100
seats. The rest seats are controlled by independents.
</P>
<P>
Khatami defended his choice of ministers by saying that
they were well-educated, excellent managers and had a record of
revolutionary activities.
</P>
<P>
Nateq-Nouri who presided over today's session said that the
deliberation will last a total of 15 hours.
</P>
<P>
Nateq-Nouri was the rival of Khatami in the presidential
elections last May. Khatami gained 20 million votes, defeating
Nateq-Nouri by 13-million-vote margin.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, Khatami submitted the list of his cabinet
ministers to the Parliament. The results of debates will be
announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed cabinet includes five ministers from the previous
administration, five with ministerial experience since 1979, and
several provincial governors.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Khatami's ministers were chosen in a
bipartisan way in a bid to appease the conservatives in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, Khatami's choice for Culture and Islamic Guidance
Minister, Ata'ollah Mohajerani, shows that Iran's new president
has stuck to his original campaign promise to foster cultural
liberalism in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani is a well-known liberal who served as Legal and
Parliamentary deputy to Rafsanjani between 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani's liberal weekly "Bahman" was forced to close in
1996 under pressure from conservatives.
</P>
<P>
To the conservatives, Mohajerani is notorious for having
supported resumption of ties with the U.S., a subject which is
considered a tabu in Iranian society after the 1979 Islamic
revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
