<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Massive Flooding Reported in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains intensified by
Typhoon "Ibiang" since Monday have caused massive flooding in the
Northern Philippines, affecting business operations and normal
lives of people in Manila and the rest of Luzon, officials said
today.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports by the official Disaster Coordination Council
said that two to three feet thick of mud water rampaged through
Pasig-Potrero river in Pamanga and two feet thick mud water at
Sacobia river in Bamban, in Central Luzon.
</P>
<P>
The 26-kilometer megadike system along both sides of
Pasig-Potrero river has remained undamaged by mud water flows so
far, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
But they said that some 10,000 families living in high-risk
areas near the river have been alerted to take precautionary
measures in case of continuous heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of Manila, thousands of families were evacuated
to schools, chapels and village halls, the Department of Social
Welfare and Development said.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the department said that the affected families,
who are living in low-lying villages in the capital city, were
evacuated early this morning as flood waters rose to chest deep.
</P>
<P>
Official disaster response operation teams are closely
monitoring the situation in Manila and other parts of the country,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The torrential rains forced some government offices, shops and
schools to close as the flooding prevented people from going to
work.
</P>
<P>
But so far, no casualties have been reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philippine Airlines canceled more domestic and
international flights scheduled for today because of the monsoon
rains.
</P>
<P>
The airlines announced that 13 domestic flights and three
international flights from Manila to Jakarta, Singapore and Kuala
Lumpur have been canceled.
</P>
<P>
Other flights bound for international destinations will operate
with some delays, it said.
</P>
<P>
Three international flights held last night and rescheduled for
today are still awaiting departure clearance. These flights are
scheduled to leave Manila for Los Angeles, Frankfurt and Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Raises Prices of all Petroleum Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
refixed the prices of all petroleum products, obviously keeping
pace with the international market as well as considering
devaluation of the country's currency Taka against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspapers, the cabinet meeting on Monday
approved the fuel prices increase, one day after the central bank
devalued Taka again in less than one month from 44 taka to 44.45
taka against one dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rate of diesel has been refixed at 12.95 taka per liter
from 12.70 taka while petrol and octane prices rose sharply to 21
taka and 23 taka from 13.70 taka and 14.65 taka respectively.
</P>
<P>
As per the new rates, each liter of kerosene has been refixed
at 12.95 taka, furnace oil 5 taka, light diesel oil 14 taka. The
government also increased the price of liquefied petroleum gas
fixing it at 250 taka per cylinder, up from 185.28 taka.
</P>
<P>
Energy Ministry officials said that the new measure would
recover the estimated loss of five billion taka (about 112 million
dollars) in the petroleum sector.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Petroleum Corporation (BPC), the lone importer of
petroleum products, placed a proposal in early June to raise the
petroleum prices.
</P>
<P>
But the cabinet turned down the proposal then considering the
hardship of the consumers and the natural effect on transport
sector, irrigation and the cost of industrial products.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the donor countries and agencies including the World
Bank have been pressing the government hard to stop the huge
subsidy in the petroleum sector by raising petroleum prices.
</P>
<P>
The price structure of widely-used petroleum products was
framed six years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
