<HEADLINE> Over 200 Kenyans Flee Violence in Mombasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 people fleeing
the violence in Kenya's southern port city of Mombasa have
arrived in capital Nairobi by train and buses, "Kenya Times"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A Mombasa politician Emmanuel Karisa Maitha was arrested
Monday in connection with the violence in Mombasa and its
environs which has led to more than 30 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The bloody violence, erupted August 13 at Likoni in Mombasa,
has spilled over to Kwale in the south of the city and Killifi
District to the north.
</P>
<P>
However, residents in the city have been assured that the
situation was under control following the third visit Monday by
Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira and a team of security
officers to the city.
</P>
<P>
Twelve suspects were charged on Monday in connection with the
initial raid at the Likoni police station, south of Mombasa
island.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from various organizations and government ministers
demanded that the Kenyan government prosecute the criminals of
the escalating violence in Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Nzamba Kitonga, Chairman of the Law Society of Kenya, called
for the arrest of the perpetrators of violence "whatever their
political persuasion".
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Monday by the Kenya section of the
International Commission of Jurists said that the government must
take full responsibility for the loss of lives in the Coast
Province over the past five days.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Lands and Settlement Noah Ngala and Minister for
Research, Technical Training and Technology Maalim Mohammed have
urged the government to bring an end to the massive loss of lives
and destruction of property caused by gangsters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
