<HEADLINE> 24 World Champs to Appear in Belgian GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- As many as 24 current world
champions will be joined by 16 Atlanta Olympic titlists as well as
such athletic old-timers as Carl Lewis and Linford Christie in the
coming Van Damme Memorial grand prix on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Leading the field will be the three world record shatterers
from the Zurich grand prix, the first of the Golden Four events.
</P>
<P>
They are Wilson Kipketer of Denmark, Haile Gebrelassie of
Ethiopia and Wilson Boit Kipketer of Kenya, who is not related to
the 800-meter runner.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian, who broke the 5,000-meter world mark, is
expected to attack the record of the 3,000-meter flat race while
Kenyan Daniel Komen, former world record holder of the 5,000
meters, required meet organizers to add his specialty to the
Belgian GP.
</P>
<P>
Joining them are also the world's fastest man and woman,
Maurice Greene and Marion Jones.
</P>
<P>
Lewis, the American sprinter with a total of nine Olympic gold
medals clutched under his belt, will not run or jump in Brussels.
He is here to bid farewell to the grand prix event, the third stop
of the Golden Four.
</P>
<P>
"There is a time to say stop," said the former world and
Olympic champion, "and I do not regret I have decided to stop."
</P>
<P>
Also present at Friday's meet will be 21 silver medalists from
the Athens' worlds and 16 bronze medalists. 
</P>
