<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Winnie Hits Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon Winnie, a strong gale
force storm hit Shanghai, China's leading industrial city, on
Monday night, with no casualties reported through this morning.
</P>
<P>
Power has been restored to affected parts of the city and
workers have reinforced dikes along the Huangpu River that flows
through Shanghai. The city's social life has basically returned to
normal, but Hongqiao Airport temporarily suspended operations.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai meteorological and water conservation departments
report that Typhoon Winnie hit the city at about 21:30 Beijing
time, with all districts and counties feeling the effects of
strong gale force winds and torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
The Pudong New Area recorded rainfall of 86 mm, with rising
water surpassing warning levels along the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
The Huangpu River Park Station scored a record high tide of
5.72 meters, a level which broke the old record by 0.5 meter.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon downed more than 40 power line poles cutting
electricity supply to thousands of homes. The one reported breach
in the river dike inundated 400 homes with 1.5 meters of water.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials of the municipal government braved the storm
to lead rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Meteorological Dept. predicts that the wind scale
will drop, but heavy and sometimes torrential rain will continue
to hit the city over the next two days. The department also
predicts high tides through August 24.  
</P>
</TEXT>
