<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese-Bangladesh Defense Chiefs Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian has expressed hope that Sino-Bangladesh friendship and
cooperation in various fields will continue to develop.
</P>
<P>
Chi made the comments this morning during a meeting this
morning with Bangladesh Defense Secretary Quazi Munjur-I-Mowla.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who also serves as a state councillor and vice-chairman of
China's Central Military Commission, said that China and
Bangladesh are close neighbors and that the both developing
countries share an unshakeable friendship based on brotherly love.
</P>
<P>
Chi noted the constant high-level visits between high-ranking
political and military leaders from the two countries and the fact
that both share either identical or similar views on major
international issues.
</P>
<P>
The development of friendship and cooperation between China and
Bangladesh and their respective armed forces is not only in the
fundamental interests of the people of both countries, but also
conducive to peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific Region and
the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Chi recounted his 1989 visit to Bangladesh and praised the
Bangladesh people for their bravery and spirit of hard work. He
noted that China and Bangladesh share a long history and brilliant
culture, and added that China can learn a lot from its friendly
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Chi said Mowla's visit will greatly enhance the development of
friendship and cooperation between the two sides. He also
expressed his appreciation for Bangladesh's just position on
issues such as human rights and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China adheres to the principle that state-to-state
relations should be guided by the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence, and that countries are equal, regardless of
whether they are big or small, strong or weak, rich or poor.
</P>
<P>
Mowia spoke highly of the Sino-Bangladesh friendship and
expressed his hope for a great success of the forthcoming 15th
National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Mowla said the goal of his visit to China is to further develop
bilateral ties and cooperation, and expressed his confidence that
the two sides will continue to increase exchanges and enhance
their long-lasting friendship and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
