<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Allow Hostile Foreign Merger, Acquisition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korean will allow hostile
merger and acquisition (M&AMP;A) of domestic firms by foreigners,
hoping this can help facilitate foreign capitals' participation in
the financially-ailing domestic business, government officials
said here.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government would strongly regulate moves
of domestic companies to jointly defend a target firm from the
hostile takeover bids as an act of collusion, said the officials
from the Ministry of Finance and Economy (MOFE).
</P>
<P>
The current rules ban hostile M&AMP;As, and friendly ones are only
allowed for enterprises with assets of less than 2 trillion won
(2.23 billion U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
New measures also include asking conglomerate owners and
executives to take the responsibility for managerial mistakes, and
punishing those involved in bribery.
</P>
<P>
In the case of the M&AMP;As of financially troubled enterprises,
the government would closely re-examine the effectiveness of the
current regulation forcing M&AMP;A carriers to buy over 50-percent
stakes in the targeted firms, noted the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Stock Index Nosedives to the year's Lowest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE) members
are expected to sit today at an emergency meeting to find out ways
for salvaging the battered market, which dived vertically on
Monday with the year's lowest index at 862.05.
</P>
<P>
Under massive selling pressure, the All Share Price Index on
Monday fell by 37.93 points to 862.05, the lowest in the last 14
months since the present government took power on June last year.
</P>
<P>
Amid the poor trading, the losing issues of the day heavily
outnumbered the gaining ones to 117-15. However, the number of
total traded issues rose to 133 from the previous day's 122.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kerb market traders continued their demonstration on
Monday in the DSE area demanding stability restoration in the
capital market.
</P>
<P>
They brought out procession chanting slogans against Finance
Minister SAMS Kibria, accusing him of not bringing in any positive
change on the market.
</P>
<P>
Stock observers said the extreme liquidity crisis in banks and
lack of institutional investors pulled down the market barometer
to such level.
</P>
<P>
A DSE member said: "We are not getting credit. We are short of
funds and we cannot absorb the sales pressure. We have lost
maneuverability."
</P>
<P>
The Securities and Exchange Commission, the regulatory
authority, should have to take some measures as soon as possible
to overcome the ongoing volatility, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
