<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teamsters Union, UPS Reach Tentative Accord to End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Teamsters union and
United Parcel Service (UPS) reached a tentative agreement tonight
to end a 15-day strike that disrupted package deliveries
nationwide, the Associated Press (AP) reported.
</P>
<P>
A news conference to announce the deal was scheduled for late
tonight, AP quoted unidentified sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The settlement followed more than 80 hours of talks since
Thursday, with pressure from Labor Secretary Alexis Herman and
some prodding from President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Details of the agreement were not immediately available, but a
source close to the talks said it was for a five-year contract
that increased the base wage for part-time workers and did not
include a contentious pension proposal made by the company, AP said.
</P>
<P>
The Teamsters, representing nearly two-thirds of UPS' 302,000
U.S. employees, went on strike August 4. Their contract expired
July 31.
</P>
<P>
Normally, UPS moves everyday 12 million bundles and parcels, or
the equivalent of five percent of the nation's gross domestic
product. But with the support of package delivery giant's 2,000
pilots, the Teamsters virtually shut the company down, leaving
business owners scrambling to find alternative carriers.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear if the workers would return to their jobs
immediately, or if they would wait for local union leaders to send
the contract out to their members for a vote.
</P>
<P>
During the strike, the Teamster Union insisted that the company
add more full-time positions. It also opposed UPS' plan to
withdraw from the Teamsters' multi-employer pension and health
funds and establish a separate benefit fund for UPS workers.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration had resisted calls from business
groups to intervene and end the strike. The White House said the
work stoppage did not pose a threat to the nation's security and
health, the standard for intervention under the 1947 Taft-Hartley
Act.
</P>
<P>
But Herman publicly urged both sides back to the bargaining
table, pressing for an end to the biggest strike in more than two
decades.
</P>
<P>
The first hint of progress came last Thursday when UPS Chief
Executive Officer James Kelly suggested the company was willing to
modify its "last, best and final offer."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Clinton said the union and the company should
"redouble their efforts and settle this strike and they ought to
do it today."
</P>
<P>
Throughout the standoff, the company had sought to bypass union
negotiators and appeal directly to employees by distributing
copies of its proposal at plant gates and through the mail, and
insisting that its final offer be put to a vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Die in Fresh Philippine Ship Wreck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Two were drowned and one missing
in a sea mishap Sunday afternoon in a central Philippine province,
bringing the death toll to 25 from a series of sea accidents last
week, a Coast Guard officer confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Commander Crisolito Agustin, regional Coast Guard operation
chief in Cebu, the central Philippines, told Xinhua by telephone
that two were rescued when a motorboat with five people on board
capsized because of strong waves in Negro Occidental province.
</P>
<P>
The boat was on its way to Bantayan Island in Cebu from
Escalante Island in Negros Occidental, Agustin said.
</P>
<P>
Agustin also confirmed that rescue operations are still going
on in rough waters near Maripipi Island in central Biliran
province, where an inter-island passenger ferry sank early Friday
morning, killing at least 12 of the 137 people on board.
</P>
<P>
He said 10 people are still missing and 12 people are still
unaccounted for. The unaccounted for include those who are
unidentified and who survived but failed to register with the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
In another tragedy last Friday, a tourist boat overturned in
Manila Bay reportedly because of strong waves, killing seven Hong
Kong tourists.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, four people died when a motorboat went down off
Talisay Island in Masbate province, the southern tip of Luzon
Island.
</P>
<P>
These sea tragedies prompted President Fidel Ramos Monday to
order the maritime industry and the departments of transportation
and communications and national defense to undertake joint efforts
to ensure safety of life at sea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
