<HEADLINE> Thailand's Unemployment Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand saw 7,607 workers laid
off during the first seven months of this year, exceeding the
5,008 recorded throughout last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase in unemployment was attributed to the country's
economic downturn, according to a report released by the Thai
Labor and Social Welfare Ministry Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 7,607 workers sacked this year, 1,403 were laid off
after the government announced the floating of the baht in early
July.
</P>
<P>
Among the sacked were many employees of the 58 finance firms
whose operations were suspended by the government in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
The ministry urged agencies concerned nationwide to set up
centers to prevent any further dismissals, while pledging to seek
every possible means to ensure that sacked workers receive
compensation according to the law.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also urged the public and private sectors to
provide low-interest loans and necessary training for those
workers sacked to help alleviate the hardship they face, while
calling on employers to seek alternative means to avoid lay-off.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
