<HEADLINE> India Launches TB Control Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
launched a national tuberculosis (TB) control program for a period
of five year with a loan of over 5 billion rupees (about 143
million U.S. dollars) from the World Bank, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The program will cover a population of 271 million in 102
districts of 15 states and union territories in the country,
according to the Indian Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis of the program is to prevent TB patients from
becoming multi-drug resistant, the ministry said in a document
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new program, the responsibility of curing a patient
has been shifted from the patient to the health worker with
directions to take health services to the doors of the
beneficiaries, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
