<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Philippines Plagued by Sea Tragedies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines still holds the
record, of course, for the worst ever sea tragedies in the world
history.
</P>
<P>
This was the sinking of the inter-island vessel Dona Paz just
four days before Christmas in 1987. The collision between the
vessel and a tanker left 4,341 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The vessel, overloaded with passengers going home to central
Leyte province for the holidays, collided with the tanker Vector.
</P>
<P>
But this month, the Philippines broke another record, perhaps
also a world record, for three sea accidents taking place within
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, strong winds and big waves overturned an
inter-island ferry, Kalibo Star, off Biliran province around
02:30, killing 12 persons and leaving at least 16 missing.
</P>
<P>
Around 15:00 that day, three people drowned and three were
missing when a small boat sank off Talisay town in Masbate.
</P>
<P>
Barely two hours later, the third tragedy occurred. A ferry
boat, King Roger, carrying 49 people, mostly tourists from Hong
Kong, China, was buffeted by strong winds and heavy waves 300
meters off the Manila Bay. Seven tourists from Hong Kong died in
the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Who should be blamed for the accidents?
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Coast Guard blamed overloading as the culprit. A
navy spokesman said that the 4.46-ton wooden-hulled King Roger was
built for only 17 people, but carried 49 people when it sank.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Kalibo Star was also overloaded with
steel bars and other construction materials, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippine Star said in an editorial: "Part of the
reason could be the government's failure to make ship operators
pay the proper price for lives lost due to greed or negligence."
</P>
<P>
"How many ship owners have been sent to jail? Does anyone even
remember who owned the inter-island ferry Dona Paz?" it asked.
</P>
<P>
"Since then, a number of major maritime disasters have also
occurred during the Christmas season, claiming hundreds of lives,"
the paper added.
</P>
<P>
A country with more than 7,000 islands, the Philippines has the
highest number of maritime accidents in Asia. A study by the Japan
International Cooperation Agency showed that the Philippines had a
yearly average of 224 sea accidents from 1982 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia had 270 accidents annually while Japan had 738
involving collisions, fire accidents and capsizing, it said.
</P>
<P>
But the number of casualties was higher in the Philippines,
where 661 people were dead or missing on a yearly average during
the 1982-1990 period. Indonesia had an average of 273 dead or
missing while Japan had 261 during the period.
</P>
<P>
The higher number of casualties in the Philippines during that
period was due to the collision of Dona Paz and the tanker Vector,
and the sinking of the ferry Marilyn in 1988.
</P>
<P>
In October 1988, about 500 people died or were missing when the
ferry Marilyn sank in a storm in the central Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Though the death toll from last Friday's three accidents was
much less compared with the 1987 and 1988 ones, the tragedies have
shocked the Philippines and the rest of the world, because of the
death of seven foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
To prevent such tragedies, the Philippine authorities have
detained Rogelio Alenzula, owner of King Roger, and its skipper
Romeo Parcon. They were charged Monday with "reckless imprudence
resulting in multiple homicide" due to the accident, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Also shocked by the tragedies, President Fidel Ramos Monday
called on the Department of Transportation and Communications, the
Department of National Defense and the entire maritime industry to
undertake joint efforts to ensure the safety of life at sea.
</P>
<P>
The local press also appealed to the people working in the
maritime industry to draw lessons from last week's tragedies by
observing safety regulations, which seem to have been often
ignored.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Foreign Minister to Push U.N. Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Foreign Minister Gennady
Udovenko says he will actively boost United Nations reforms during
his tenure as the president of the 52nd U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko told the Russian Interfax news agency that
U.N. reforms should, firstly, focus on strengthening its role in
handling a range of priority issues, such as peace, security and
disarmament as well as economic, social, humanitarian, ecological
and human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
The 52nd U.N. General Assembly is scheduled to open on
September 16 in New York, and is supposed to work out steps for
the materialization of U.N. reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, the reforms would be no easy tasks since different
member countries or groups had their own interests, Udovenko noted.
</P>
<P>
With the end of the "Cold War" period, the United Nations
should reposition itself, Udovenko added. As the would-be
president for the U.N. General Assembly, he saw himself shouldering
heavy responsibilities in the fulfillment of reforms already
underway.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko will continue to be the Ukrainian Foreign Minister
while he serves as the the president of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said he would take an objective attitude towards various
issues discussed at the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Ukraine had a special interest in developing
relations with countries in Africa, South Asia and the Pacific
region, Udovenko added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
