<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Displaced Tamils Keep Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- About 800 displaced Sri Lankan
Tamils who are stranded at Trincomalee town in the east Monday
launched a fast, demanding that the government immediately send
them back to Jaffna Peninsula in the north.
</P>
<P>
They are among the 8,000 persons registered with the government
to return to Jaffna but have been stranded in Trincomalee as the
passenger boat service to Jaffna has been suspended since July 3,
according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
There are reportedly about 2,000 others waiting for transport
to Jaffna Peninsula from Trincomalee town.
</P>
<P>
Since August last year, about 60,000 persons had been
transported to Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
But with the suspension of the boat service in July, many have
been stranded in and around Trincomalee.
</P>
<P>
The owners of the vessels are unwilling to expose the safety of
their vessels and crew to possible attacks by the Tamil rebels who
have been fighting for a separate state in the north and east of
the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that those who had left their home due to the
fighting and were waiting for transport to the north, were mainly
teachers, students, workers, elderly persons and children.
</P>
</TEXT>
