<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Develop Indigenous Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
planning to develop the cultivation of indigenous medicinal plants
and herbs for which there is an increased demand locally and a
vibrant export market in Western countries, particularly Europe.
</P>
<P>
According to Ministry of Forestry and Environment sources
today, the ministry has granted 6.8 million U.S. dollars to
develop the cultivation and embark on a home garden medicinal
plant and herb cultivation program in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the ministry are touring the country conducting
awareness programs in the villages. An awareness program was held
at Kataragama, about 200 kilometers south of Colombo last week,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A survey reveals that Sri Lanka spends as much as 500,000 U.S.
dollars annually on the import of indigenous medicines and this
valuable foreign exchange could be conserved with the development
of the cultivation of indigenous medicinal plants and herbs.
</P>
<P>
The sources said there was a significant shift among Westerners
to Eastern indigenous treatment.
</P>
<P>
Hence, there was also great export potential for Eastern
indigenous medicines, they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
