<HEADLINE> Thai PM Sets Roles for Top Aides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has set roles for his deputies in line with the
Cabinet reshuffle last Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to an order by Chavalit at the government's economic
ministers meeting Monday, Deputy Prime Minister Virabhongsa
Ramangjura is assigned to oversee economic affairs of the country,
filling the vacancy left by former deputy prime minister Amnuay
Virawan who resigned on June 19 this year.
</P>
<P>
Virabhongsa, will administer the finance and commerce
ministries as well as affairs involving international trade.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra, who served as one of
the deputy prime ministers in charge of Bangkok's traffic affairs
during the previous government, this time saw a major change for
his role in the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit Monday assigned Thaksin to supervise the country's
National Economic and Social Development Board, tourism and
economic cooperation with neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today said that Thaksin's first job is
expected to re-examine Thailand's eighth national economic and
social development plan.
</P>
<P>
The local telecommunications tycoon also is responsible for
policies related to the economy and monitor the progress of the
International Monetary Fund's bailout package.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Sukhavich Rangsitpol is added a new role
to oversee sports affairs in the country in addition to his old
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The sports affairs was previously supervised by Chingchai
Mongkoltham who replaced Sukhavich as education minister during
the Friday reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
King Bhumibol Adulyadej issued a royal decree last Friday,
approving the Cabinet reshuffle list proposed by Chavalit, in
which Virabhongsa and Thaksin were appointed deputy prime
ministers and Sukhavich was removed from his post of education
minister but retained his deputy premiership.
</P>
<P>
Some ministers or deputy ministers were also changed during the
reshuffle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
