<HEADLINE> Panama, U.S. Discuss Joint Canal Area Cleaning-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Ministry of
Panama is negotiating with the U.S. government to jointly clean up
the much polluted Canal area, the Interoceanic Authority (ARI)
director Nicolas Ardito Barletta said today.
</P>
<P>
The ARI, together with the Institute of Natural Replaceable
Resources, serves as the advisor to the Foreign Ministry in the
negotiations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1977 treaty between the two countries, the United
States will hand over the administration of the Canal to Panama on
December 31, 1999, together with eight military bases along the
banks of the Canal.
</P>
<P>
The ARI leader said the worst polluted spots are the New
Emperor near the Pacific, and Pina and Sherman on the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
But the areas inhabited mainly by U.S. citizens for decades are
pollution free, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
