<HEADLINE> Ukrainian PM: Understand Domestic Situations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Valeriy
Pustovoitenko stressed the need for government officials to
understand domestic situations at a press conference today after
he visited Poltava and Sumy Oblasts on August 15 and 16.
</P>
<P>
He said he will make frequent working trips to the regions of
the country and also send his subordinates down there.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Pustovoitenko toured the Akhtyrka Oil and Gas
Company in Sumy. The Akhtyrka oil field, which has been exploited
since 1961, accounts for 50 percent of oil and about eight percent
of natural gas extracted in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
He hoped to extend the life-span of the oil field to at least
50 years with an average oil production of 2.5 million tons every
year.
</P>
<P>
In view of continuously shrinking imports of Russian crude oil
to Ukraine, which once accounted for 80 percent of Ukraine's
consumption but now barely reach 40 percent, he viewed domestic
oil extraction as an increasingly vital factor to national
security.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Akhtyrka oil field, the Ukrainian prime minister
also visited the Sumy Chemical Production Company, which is
Ukraine's largest manufacturer of phosphate fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister blamed some of his Cabinet
members for traveling abroad instead of visiting local provinces
to gather first-hand information.
</P>
<P>
"Some ministers are just frightened by the very idea of making
a trip to any particular region of Ukraine," said Pustovoitenko.
</P>
</TEXT>
