<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0000 GMT, August 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO -- NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) confirmed on
Monday that its troops had been developed around the Banja Luka
police station to prevent a potential clash between rival Serb
police. Major John Blakeley, a spokesman for SFOR, said that after
50 Serb special policemen loyal to Republika Srpska President
Biljana Plavsic took over the Banja Luka public security center in
a predawn raid on Sunday, Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb member of
the Bosnia presidency asked SFOR for permission to use other
special police units for "operational reason". (Bosnia-Police)
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government has expressed its readiness to
help evacuate the remaining residents of the Caribbean island of
Montserrat as experts warned that a massive volcanic eruption was
approaching. Officials from the British Foreign Office and the
Overseas Development Office were reportedly holding urgent talks
on the worsening situation in the island, which has been
repeatedly attacked by a series of volcanic eruptions.
(UK-Montserrat-Volcano)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman said here Monday
that China is an important country which is full of promise and
her development is a great contribution to the world.
</P>
<P>
Weizman made the remarks during his meeting with Guo Chaoren,
president of China's Xinhua News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Guo arrived here Sunday heading a Xinhua delegation for a
three-day visit at the invitation of the Israeli foreign ministry.
(Israel-Weizman)
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Six Lebanese civilians were killed and 28 others
seriously injured Monday in shelling by the Israeli troops and its
allied militiamen, the South Lebanon Army (SLA), the official
Lebanese News Agency reported. Among the dead were a one-month-old
girl, a six-year-old boy and a woman, and most of the injured are
in serious conditions. (Lebanon-Shelling-Deaths)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States is undermining an international
treaty on banning all nuclear test by working hard at updating the
design of its nuclear arms, said a report to be released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Declassified excerpts from an Energy Department document that
includes the government's plan to improve the reliability of its
nuclear weapons arsenal were first reported Monday's editions of
The New York Times. (US-Nuclear-Report)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. government believes that China has taken
no action to violate its commitment on arms sales, the State
Department said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that China has taken no actions that we have been
able to confirm to violate the commitment it's made on May 11,
1996," said spokesman James Rubin at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to an allegation by Washington Times Saturday
that China has violated a pledge not to provide nuclear weapons
materials to facilities in Pakistan operating without
international safeguards.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the story "fundamentally and seriously
misquoted" a report from the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament
Agency (ACDA) and "completely got it 180 degrees wrong."
</P>
<P>
The ACDA report said, "China stated that it would provide no
assistance to unsafeguarded nuclear facilities. Our current
information does not provide a basis for concluding that China has
acted inconsistently with that statement." (US-Rubin-China)
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Tajik government is now oriented toward resolving
the conflict by force because its peace initiatives have proved
unsuccessful, Tajik presidential spokesman Zafar Saidov stated
Monday in Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik government forces Monday launched a new offensive on
the positions of mutinous colonel Makhmud Khudoiberdyev and seized
a strategic bridge in the area of Garavuti, according to a report
reaching here from Dushanbe, Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
In the fierce battle for the bridge, government forces hit five
units of the enemy's armored equipment, destroyed three
antiaircraft installations and one howitzer. (Tajikistan-Fighting)
</P>
</TEXT>
