<HEADLINE> Investors Compete Equally in Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Everyone is competing equally
under the control of a unified national treatment in Xiamen, a
city in southeast China's Fujian province, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes Hong Yongshi, mayor of Xiamen as saying that
they no longer count on preferential policies. Xiamen was
designated as a special economic zone (SEZ) in 1981 and has
established the basic framework for a market economy.
</P>
<P>
About 90 local laws have been put into effect to manage the
economy and protect investors' interests. Hong emphasized that
Xiamen has also converted into a modern city that meets with
international norms and practices in business dealings.
</P>
<P>
During the past 16 years, investment in fixed assets has
grown to 6.94 billion US dollars, forming a significant basis.
</P>
<P>
A modern network of transportation and telecommunications is in
place to connect the island with the outside world, and the
airport is among the best managed in the country, according to
Hong.
</P>
<P>
Three of the four Taiwan Investment Zones, established to
attract investments from the island, are located in Xiamen, having
attracted more than 1,300 projects since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Last year, foreign trade volume of the city reached 6.65
billion US dollars, ranking the fourth among the 35 large- and
medium-sized cities in the country, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
