<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firms Win Three Gorges Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese companies have
been awarded 807 million US dollars worth of contracts for the
second phase of the gigantic Three Gorges project, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The three companies were Gezhouba Share Holding Ltd, Yichang
Qingyun Hydropower Joint Management Co, and Yichang Three Gorges
Project Construction 378 Joint Management.
</P>
<P>
After heated competition, the companies won contracts for the
construction and installation of the dam and power plant
workshops, the most expensive portion of the project.
</P>
<P>
According to the contracts, the three companies will build a
flood discharge dike, ground workshops and power plant workshops,
and dikes on the left bank.
</P>
<P>
The construction work is expected to involve the excavation of
approximately 8 million cubic meters of earth and stone, the
pouring of 12.4 million cubic metres of concrete, and the
installation of 148,700 tons of equipment and metal structure.
</P>
<P>
Officials said results of the bidding for contracts to sell the
first 14 power-generating units to the Three Gorges project will
be announced in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project will have three phase. The first
phase, kicked off in 1993, will finish damming the Yangstze River
across Xiling Gorge this November.
</P>
<P>
The second phase will last six years and will build a reservoir
for flood control and power generating. Eventually, the reservoir
is expected to offer a place for sailing.
</P>
<P>
The whole project is expected to be completed by 2009, and is
expected to cost about 200 billion yuan (24.1 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The project will be capable of holding 22.1 billion cubic
meters of floodwater to protect 15 million people and 1.5 million
hectares of farmland. It is expected to generate 84.7 billion
kilowatts-hour of power annually to supply China's growing demand
for electricity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
