<HEADLINE> German Hempel Wins Platform Diving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Jan Hempel of Germany took the
men's platform diving gold medal at the European Swimming
Championships in Seville, Spain on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hempel recieved the coveted title dispite the fact that he had
been suffering from influenza for three days.
</P>
<P>
He earned a lone perfect 10 points, three 9.5 points, and three
9.0s with a total of 609.48 for the crown.
</P>
<P>
After taking the silver in 1987, 1989 and 1995 and bronze in
1993, he had finally added a platform gold to the European
three-meter springboard title which he won in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Joroslav Makogin of Ukraine took the silver with 600.48 and
Hempel's compatriot Heiko Meyer came to the third at 571.44.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Sports Chief Reacts Angrily to Attack on Rome's Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rome, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Italian sports chief Mario Pescante
today responded angrily to a sharp attack on Rome's campaign to
host the 2004 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Pescante, president of the Italian Olympic Committee, said
articles such as the one in the Milan daily Corriere della Sera on
Friday, "are acts of terrorism, more serious, more dangerous than
the bombs which exploded in Stockholm."
</P>
<P>
The Mayor of Rome, Francesco Rutelli, and the head of the Rome
2004 committee, Raffacle Ranucci, have both announced libel suits
against the newspaper and the author of the article, Ernesto Galli
della Loggia.
</P>
<P>
Loggia in the article claimed that the only way to win the
right to stage the Games was by bribing members of the
International Olympic Committee (IOC), and he speculated that
those promoting Rome's candidacy were engaged in such "dirty work".
</P>
<P>
Pescante said the damage done by the article would be
considerable, "We give the impression of a country in which debate
has fallen to the lowest level, to that of trashy article."
</P>
<P>
The IOC is due to decide on September 5 which city will host
the 2004 Games. Other short-listed candidates are Athens, Buenos
Aires, Cape Town and Stockholm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
