<HEADLINE> Pakistan for Sustained Dialogue with India: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari expressed his hope that a sustained and structured
dialogue between Pakistan and India would address all outstanding
issues between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want confrontation and we believe that with
sincerity and serious purpose, all outstanding issues including
the Kashmir dispute can be resolved through peaceful means,"
Leghari said when he met with a U.S. congressional delegation
here.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Leghari and the U.S. congressional
delegation exchanged views on the regional situation and
Pakistan's relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
He briefed the delegation on recent development in
Pakistan-India relations and emphasized that the recent decision
of the Pakistani government to initiate dialogue with India was a
positive development.
</P>
<P>
About Afghanistan, Leghari said the fratricidal conflict was
adding to the miseries of the Afghan nation.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan being a neighboring state was interested in the
restoration of peace and stability in Afghanistan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Explaining Pakistan's policy towards Afghanistan, the President
said: "We have no favorites and therefore we have no preference
for one group over the other."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he added, supports intra-Afghan dialogue for the
establishment of a broad-based government, representative of all
ethnic groups in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to extend full support to the efforts of the U.N.
for restoration of peace and reconciliation in Afghanistan," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about Pakistan-U.S. relations, Leghari said both
countries have a long history of friendship and such relationship
will be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
The visiting U.S. congressmen said that as a body, the Congress
desires to maintain and encourage good relations with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The congressmen said they value the long standing relations
with Pakistan which despite some ups and downs remains an
important partner for the U.S.  
</P>
