<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Banks Do Not Expect Major Rate Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Federation of German
Banks said today that it does not expect any major increases in
German interest rates for the time being.
</P>
<P>
In its August economic report, the German banks group predicted
that the German central bank, the Bundesbank, was likely to
tighten up money supply cautiously in the next few months "in
order to avoid overreaction on the markets."
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank might limit its move to just raising the
securities repurchase rate which applies to short-term liquidity
provided to banks, the federation said.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank has threatened to raise interest rates in order
to arrest strong rises in consumer prices and check the German
mark's steady decline against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Despite the threat, it chose to leave the repurchase rate
unchanged at 3.0 percent on August 12. The two benchmark rates,
the discount rate and the Lombard rate, have also been left intact
at historical lows for over one year.
</P>
<P>
It is widely assumed that a rate increase in Germany carries
the risk that it could choke economic growth and undermine Bonn's
efforts to combat unemployment higher than 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The weak German mark, which has fallen about 18 percent against
the dollar so far this year, makes imports to Germany more
expensive but helps the export sector that has been so crucial to
Germany's nascent recovery from a five-year economic slump.
</P>
<P>
Due to declining labor costs and relatively stable growth in
money supply, German banks did not see any acute inflation danger
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
They also saw little danger of major increases in long-term
interest rates in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
