<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Joint Efforts to Resolve Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The British government today
appealed to the international community to make joint efforts to
put an end to the stalemate of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after talks with UN mediator and special Cyprus envoy
Diego Cordovez today, Britain's Foreign Office minister Doug
Henderson said, "We are all determined that the parties should
continue to be brought together and a solution should be sought
for this difficult situation."
</P>
<P>
"We are determined that the situation should not be allowed to
fester. All countries must bring their best endeavors to try to
help specific parts of the negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, a former British colony, became an independent republic
in 1960 and entered the British Commonwealth in 1961. The island's
Greek and Turkish communities have been locked in fierce disputes
and armed clashes over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, which stationed international peacekeeping
forces in Cyprus since 1964, has been trying to find a proper
solution to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Henderson noted that the Cyprus people should realize that the
time had come for them to bury their enmity and start living
together in peace.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Cyprus have to recognize this is a changing
situation and that they need to make the changes in the same way
changes have been made in other parts of the world," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Cordovez, who is due to visit Cyprus
later this year, said, "I feel that support from Britain and other
governments has to continue. If we maintain consultations and
adopt a coherent approach, we can get out of this problem."
</P>
</TEXT>
