<HEADLINE> German Economy on Course for 2.5 Percent Growth: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- German economy is expanding at a
pace which will enable the government to meet its earlier
projections of 2.5 percent growth for 1997, the German economics
minister said today.
</P>
<P>
According to Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt, the German
economy grew by 1 percent in the second quarter from the previous
quarter and was up between 2.5 percent and 3.0 percent from a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
This would bring Germany's gross domestic product (GDP) growth
to 2 percent in the first half of 1997, corresponding with Bonn's
projections of 2.5 percent growth for the whole year and 2.5 to 3
percent for 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
While domistic demand remained weak, German exports continued
to expand and were expected to grow faster than the growth of
world trade in 1997, Rexrodt said.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that German unemployment was still on the
increase and could only expect a modest decline next year.
</P>
<P>
The overall unemployment was likely to be over 4.3 million in
1997, up 350,000 from the previous year. The government expected
joblessness to decline by 100,000 in 1998, Rexrodt said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
