<HEADLINE> Germany Warns Kenya Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Germany today warned people
visiting Kenya of "the dramatically worsening security situation"
there, advising them in particular not to travel to the northeast
area of Kenya, where crimes are prevalent.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry also suggested that travelers should avoid
the area between Malindi and Lamu where Somali gangs are active.
</P>
<P>
"With the start of election campaigns, regional and limited
acts of violent conflict linked with opposition and student
demonstrations must be expected," said the ministry in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The capital of Nairobi and the port city of Mombasa are high
crime areas and tourists should avoid both city centers after
dark, in addition to all overland roads, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 30 people have been killed in a
series of attacks in and around Mombasa over the past week.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists in Kenya are facing growing street crime,
robbery, assault and car-jackings, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The German Foreign Ministry also voiced opposition to travel by
car north of the entrances to the Samburu National park and to the
Shava National Reserve in regions north of Lake Baringo and
Kitale.
</P>
<P>
People intended to visit Lake Turkana should only travel there
by air, it added.
</P>
<P>
It meanwhile noted that it was not telling tourists to stay
away from Kenya, saying, "There is no general travel warning for
Kenya."
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 German tourists visit Kenya each year, it was
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
