<HEADLINE> Dow Bounces Back From 76 Points Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street bounced
back today, with a burst of buying by bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
The Dow rebounded over the final two hours of trading, erasing
a 76-point slide and then rising 108.70 to 7,803.36.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a slim margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 517.16 million
shares as against 530.34 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market measures also rallied into the close, led by the
technology group, which had been struggling after a disappointing
profit report from Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list, rose 11.68 to 912.49.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index, which lost nearly 25 points Friday,
rebounded from a 16-point loss today and rose 7.49 to 1,569.52.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 4.45 to 473.55, but the American
Stock Exchange composite index slipped 0.02 to 634.59.
</P>
<P>
The session started smoothly, with most indexes edging higher
as bargain hunters tried to take advantage of Friday's sharp
decline.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that even with Friday's 247-point slide -- the
Dow's second biggest point drop ever after the 508-point Black
Monday crash of October 19, 1987 -- the famed blue-chip gauge is
still up more than 19 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
No rate hike is expected at Tuesday's Opening Committee meeting
of the Federal Reserve, but central bank officials could take
action when they meet again in September. 
</P>
