<HEADLINE> US Welcomes Israel's Partial Transfer of Tax Refunds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
welcomed Israel's decision to release 30 percent of tax refunds to
the Palestinians, and pressed on the Israelis to lift all the ban
to that tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
"We welcomed this decision. We believe this is a step in the
right direction.... We feel a little better today than we did
yesterday about the prospects for getting the peace process back
on track," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
approved the transfer of 30 percent of the refunds -- 12 million
dollars -- it has frozen after the July 30 suicide bombing attack
at a Jerusalem market that killed 14 Israelis and two bombers.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's decision came after the Palestinians began to help
the Israelis in the bombing investigation, the prime minister's
chief adviser David Dar Illan said. "We got the information we
asked for on the terrorist strike."
</P>
<P>
But 12 million dollars was far less than the 70 million dollars
Israel owes to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"We don't accept these compromises," Palestinian Economics
Minister Maher Masri said. "We need to be paid in full, and we
need to be paid on time."
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said it was "counterproductive" by withholding the
tax revenue, and the United States believes the money should be
released now. "We think that is not the best way to encourage
cooperation" by withholding the money, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
