<HEADLINE> Rubin: China Has Not Violated Commitment on Arms Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government believes
that China has taken no action to violate its commitment on arms
sales, the State Department announced here today.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that China has taken no actions that we have been
able to confirm to violate the commitment it's made on May 11,
1996," said spokesman James Rubin at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to an allegation by Washington Times Saturday
that China has violated a pledge not to provide nuclear weapons
materials to facilities in Pakistan operating without
international safeguards.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the story "fundamentally and seriously
misquoted" a report from the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament
Agency (ACDA) and "completely got it 180 degrees wrong."
</P>
<P>
The ACDA report said, "China stated that it would provide no
assistance to unsafeguarded nuclear facilities. Our current
information does not provide a basis for concluding that China has
acted inconsistently with that statement."
</P>
<P>
"He (the Washington Times reporter) wrote the opposite," Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
"Our view, unlike the view quoted and attributed to the United
States government, is that we believe that China has taken no
action to violate that commitment," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
China has consistently stated its opposition to weapons
proliferation and taken part in varied worldwide disarmament
activities. In recent years, China and the U.S. have conducted
dialogues on the non-proliferation issue in order to seek a common
ground for cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
