<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: US Development of Nukes Undermines Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
undermining an international treaty on banning all nuclear test by
working hard at updating the design of its nuclear arms, said a
report to be released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Declassified excerpts from an Energy Department document that
includes the government's plan to improve the reliability of its
nuclear weapons arsenal were first reported in today's editions of
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
The document obtained by the Natural Resources Defense Council,
a private organization in Washington that advocates arms control
and monitors U.S. arms programs, states, "The laboratories are
currently working on programs to provide new or modified designs."
</P>
<P>
The arms control group distributed copies of its own report,
End Run, citing the declassified document of the Energy
Department. The group planned to make the report public at a news
conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"While the U.S. government is not now designing or producing
advanced new types of nuclear weapons, it is enlarging its
capabilities to do so, while continuing to design nuclear
explosive packages to replace warheads on existing systems such as
the Navy's Trident II missiles," said Christopher Paine, a
co-author of the report.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, Paine and his partner Matthew McKinzie said
that some of the ongoing and planned activities of the U.S.
administration come into conflict with its policies on nuclear
test ban.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. sought and achieved both the indefinite extension of
the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty in 1995 and the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty in 1996, partly on the strength of assurances that
it would not design new nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Paine said the document, Stockpile Stewardship and Management
Program, shows that the U.S. is still operating as if the Cold War
has not ended.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the U.S. government is planning to
develop within the coming decade comprehensive three-dimensional,
computer simulations of nuclear weapons performance, a "virtual
testing" capability.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to design, simulate, and flight-test
weapon prototypes, and certify both the nuclear and
stockpile-to-target performance of new weapon designs as possible
replacements for existing stockpile weapons.
</P>
<P>
"If implemented over the next decade as planned," said Paine,
"this program is poised to erode important U.S. non-proliferation
objectives as well as undermine political assurances the U.S.
government has supplied to other nations."
</P>
<P>
However, Energy Department officials insist the plans described
in the document only modernize old designs. They said the goals
include increasing the life of warheads and their safety and
security but not their explosive power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Agrees to Join Negotiations on Land Mines Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced
today that it will participate in negotiations to agree on a
150-nation treaty banning antipersonnel land mines by year's end.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the U.S. government will continue to work on
establishing a global ban through a U.N. Conference on
Disarmament, a longer process it prefers to the country-by-country
treaty, the White House said in a statement from Martha's
Vineyard, where President Bill Clinton and his family began a
three-week vacation Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation in the Conference on Disarmament on new steps in
this area remains essential since that body's membership includes
most of the major producers and exporters of antipersonnel land
mines," White House spokesman Barry Toiv said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is committed to pursuing the most promising
opportunities for ending the use of antipersonnel land mines,
which every year cause enormous suffering around the world."
</P>
<P>
The United States had been holding out for negotiating only the
global deal through the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The proposed 150-nation treaty, to be negotiated further in
Ottawa, Canada, beginning September 1 and signed by December,
would ban mines designed to kill and injure people. But it would
not ban antipersonnel mines meant to stop tanks or other military
vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
