<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Dept. Report Shows Women Percentage  Increasing in Criminal Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The latest Justice Department
report shows that a growing percentage of the adults on probation
and parole across the United States are women.
</P>
<P>
Although men still commit many more crimes, there has been a
"dramatic increase in the number of women arrested" over the past
decade, The Washington Post today quoted an official of the
department's Bureau of Justice Statistics as saying.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were more than 650,000 women on probation, 21
percent of all probationers, and 79,000 women on parole, 11
percent of that total. In 1990, women made up 18 percent of all
probationers and 8 percent of all parolees.
</P>
<P>
The report said there were almost 3.9 million adults on
probation or parole at the end of 1996, an increase of 3.4 percent
from the year before. Another 1.6 million were locked up in jail
or prison, putting the total correctional population in the
country at a record 5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Officials said there has been an increasing use of
incarceration since 1985, when only one of four adults under
correctional supervision was in jail or prison. In 1996, the ratio
was three to 10.
</P>
<P>
Overall, women accounted for 17 percent of all arrests in 1986
and 20 percent in 1995, the most recent year of which those
numbers are available. Fraud, larceny, theft and drug offenses are
more prevalent among women than men.
</P>
<P>
The study also shows more probationers and parolees are being
locked up for new offenses. In 1996, 18 percent of all
probationers released for supervision were later incarcerated for
a rule violation or a new crime, compared with 8 percent in 1985.
Forty percent of those exiting parole were put behind bars again,
compared with 35 percent in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970819.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US: DPRK Light-Water Reactor Ground-Breaking "Milestone" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
called Tuesday's ground-breaking of the construction of the
light-water nuclear reactors in the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) "an important milestone" to achieve the
denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"We think that it increases the chances that North Korea's
nuclear program will stay frozen and ultimately be dismantled,"
State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK agreed to dismantle its graphite nuclear reactors in
1994 on condition that the United States and its allies should
help build two light-water reactors.
</P>
<P>
And the United States, South Korea and Japan have since formed
a consortium, called the Korean Energy Development Organization,
to provide about 5 billion dollars for the project.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the DPRK's freeze and dismantling of its nuclear
program is "monitored by the International Atomic Energy Agency,
and "it is nearing completion of a project with the United States
to safely store its spent nuclear fuel" of the graphite reactors.
</P>
<P>
"The bargain that we struck with North Korea is working," Rubin
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
